<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ranariddh Confirms Creating New Party Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's First Prime
Minister Norodom Ranariddh today confirmed he involved in
creating a new party alliance to contest in this year's local
elections and next year's general elections.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh, president of the Funcinpec Party, said he is
ready to set up the National United Front "which would be open to
all."
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the closing ceremony of a seminar
at the law faculty, he said, "It is not an alliance against this
or that," and even his party's chief rival, the Cambodian People's
Party, (CPP) would be allowed to join.
</P>
<P>
"All really patriotic Cambodians should join," he said,
promising that every member party of the Front will retain its
own "identity and autonomy."
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh, who made the announcement on the eve of a CPP
congress, said a charter for the front has been worked
out and approved by the Funcinpec Party, the Khmer National Party
(KNP) led by former Finance Minister Sam Rainsy, and the
Democratic National Union Movement under the leadership of Ieng
Sary, who broke away from the Khmer Rouge last August.
</P>
<P>
A faction of the Buddhist Liberal Democratic Party led by its
founder Son Sann, and the Khmer Neutral Party, are studying the
charter, but are expected to join, the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh said that he would personally present the charter to
Chea Sim, CPP president and president of the National Assembly, to
see "if the CPP is able to join the front."
</P>
<P>
KNP president Sam Rainsy said in a press statement today that
"the Khmer National Party confirms that it is prepared to join the
National United Front." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
