<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Housing Reform Goals Set For 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, January 23 (Xinhua) -- State Councillor Li Tieying
said today that China will encourage housing growth and increased
investment in state housing projects this year so as to set up a
new housing system compatible with the socialist market economy by
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Li, who is a member of the Political Bureau of the Communist
Party of China's Central Committee and head of the State Council's
Housing Reform Leading Group, made the remarks at a national
conference on housing reforms in Chengdu, the capital of Sichuan
Province.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, China had 39.3 billion yuan (about 4.7
billion US dollars) in housing funds and rent per square-metre of
space had grown to between 0.8 and 1.5 yuan.
</P>
<P>
In some cities, authorities lowered housing prices to near
construction costs, and the Comfortable Housing Project, a
state-funded project to provide affordable housing for people with
inadequate living space, went smoothly.
</P>
<P>
In 1995 and the first half of 1996, the project got 28.79
billion yuan in state funds, and 23.77 million sq.m. in housing,
were completed, 19.16 million of which sold.
</P>
<P>
Li told the conference that the housing system reforms in 1997
should try to make progress in a stable and appropriate way, and
that the old system of distributing houses as a kind of welfare
should be gradually abolished in a planned way.
</P>
<P>
He pointed to the importance of improving the collection, use,
management, and supervision of the housing fund, and said that
primary task in housing reforms in 1997 and afterwards is ensuring
the safety and proper use of the fund.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that this year the central government has
plans to increase its loans to the Comfortable Housing Project by
10 billion yuan, most of which will go to cities with a good
record of housing reforms and in carrying out the project.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
