<HEADLINE> Egypt: No Foreign Help in Probes on Letter Bombs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has not and will not
request any foreign assistance in the investigations into letter
bombs found in the United States, Egyptian Minister of Interior
Hassan Mohamed al-Alfy said today.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks during a visit to Egypt's Police
Academy here, rejecting a report that foreign security experts
were sought for help.
</P>
<P>
Al-Alfy said the cooperation in this case is no more than an
exchange of information with the United States.
</P>
<P>
Nine letter bombs bearing postal marks from the Mediterranean
Sea resort of Alexandria, north of Egypt, were sent to offices of
the Arabic-language Al-Hayat newspaper in Washington and New York
and other places of the United States early this month.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has categorically denied any letter bombs went out of
Alexandria, suggesting that the stamps were fake.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is conducting the investigations on its own, the
interior minister said, adding that the exchange of information
and the receipt of the original copies of the letter bombs are
necessary. It has also asked the U.S. to track the course of the
letter bombs inside the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
