<HEADLINE> US Weekly Jobless Claims Hit A 10-month High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The number of new claims for
jobless benefits shot up by 34,000 in the U.S. last week, the
biggest jump in 10 months, the Labor Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that new applications for unemployment
insurance totaled a seasonally adjusted 355,000, up from 321,000
during the week ended January 11.
</P>
<P>
The increase was the steepest since new claims rose by 47,000
during the week ended on March 23 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Many analysts attributed the increase in part to volatility
often associated with end-of-year problems in adjustments for
seasonal variations.
</P>
<P>
The four-week moving average of new weekly jobless claims in
the country rose by 2,750 to 353,750, highest since 358,250 during
the period ended January 4, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The four-week average is closely watched since it smooths out
the spikes in the volatile weekly reports.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. economy is growing moderately which should result in
tighter job markets and fewer jobless claims. The U.S. government
reported earlier this month that 262,000 new jobs were created in
December, the most in seven months.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Reserve survey announced on Wednesday also
disclosed numerous instances of labor shortages, particularly
among skilled workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
