<HEADLINE> France to Build 2 Conventionally Powered Submarines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 23 (Xinhua) -- France will build for Chile two
"Scorpion Fish" class conventionally powered submarines at a
value of 2.5 billion francs (500 million U.S. dollars), announced
the French military today.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Yves Helmer, General Delegate of Armament of the French
Army, was quoted as saying that France has been chosen by the
Chilean government to negotiate a contract on building the two
1,400-ton new design submarines for the Chilean Navy.
</P>
<P>
"The Chilean authorities have expressed their preference to a
proposal by the DCN (state navy industrial company of France). We
have good hope of concluding the contract in the coming months,"
said Helmer.
</P>
<P>
The German company HDW, Swedish Kockums and some British firms
were beat by the DCN in the bidding for the contract, according to
the Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
The DCN International, the affiliate of the DCN in charge of
exporting warships, proposed to Chile that it would use some
newest technologies for nuclear-powered submarines in designing
the two combat vessels, particularly the technology for
maintaining silence of their movement.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish naval company Empresa Nacional Bazan also will win
a sub-contract in the deal, which will be realized in a French
naval dockyard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
