<HEADLINE> Chinese Journalists Urged to Improve Ethics (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 23 (Xinhua) -- A nationwide TV and telephone
conference today discussed Chinese journalists' professionalism
and ethics and avoiding "paid news".
</P>
<P>
The conference was jointly sponsored by the Propaganda
Department of the Communist Party of China's Central Committee,
the Ministry of Radio, Film, and Television, the Press and
Publication Administration of China, and the All-China
Journalists' Association.
</P>
<P>
Participants said that, since the sixth plenum of the 14th CPC
Central Committee last October, ethical and cultural progress in
China has been advanced. They agreed that, as the publicizers and
promoter of a nationwide campaign, journalists should be models of
socialist ethical and cultural progress, instead of mere
supervisors.
</P>
<P>
Recently, ten major service sectors, including the railways,
public security, and posts and telecommunications, took the lead
in announcing criteria for "civilized services", and launched a
campaign of "serving the people and improving professional ethics".
</P>
<P>
Zheng Mengxiong, executive vice-president of the All-China
Journalists' Association, said that there is now a revised version
of the "Code of Professional Ethics for Chinese Journalists", and
Liang Heng, deputy director of the Press and Publication
Administration, read the full text of "Regulations On
Forbidding 'Paid News'", agreed upon by the four sponsoring
organizations.
</P>
<P>
"Generally Speaking, China's press corps are good, and the
majority of the journalists are strict with themselves, do a clean
job, and get favorable comments from the general public," the
participants noted.
</P>
<P>
However, they conceded that with the new conditions of setting
up a socialist market economy, some new problems have arisen and
some members of the press are still turning out "paid news"
regardless of the ban.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Journalists Urged to Improve Ethics (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Even though the problem of 'paid news' only involved a small
number of people, it has done great harm by corrupting
journalists, tarnishing their reputation, and affecting the nature
of socialist journalism," they noted.
</P>
<P>
They went on to say that "paid news", which is against
journalistic principles, professional ethics, the Party
leadership, and the ideology of serving the people has had a very
bad effect on society, and has been strongly opposed by both the
general public and by most journalists.
</P>
<P>
Journalists across China were urged to carefully study a speech
by President Jiang Zemin during a visit to the country's leading
newspaper, People's Daily, where he called on journalists to
"strictly follow professional ethics and firmly oppose 'paid
news'", putting an end to the practice.
</P>
<P>
"Journalists must try to create a sound public image for
themselves by means of self-discipline and by putting themselves
under the supervision of the whole society," said the participants.
</P>
<P>
Journalists across the country were also asked to closely study
the two documents from today's conference and to try to establish
an effective system that awards those who comply and censures
those who do not.
</P>
<P>
"Journalists should correctly handle the relation between
social benefit and financial profit, news coverage and the market
economy, self-discipline and supervision by others, and
ideological education and disciplinary punishment," they said,
adding that the elimination of "paid news" should be regarded as a
key part of one's political awareness and readiness to serve the
people whole-heartedly.
</P>
<P>
Xu Guangchun, deputy head of the Propaganda Department of the
CPC Central Committee, said that 41 news units across the country
have been chosen as "demonstration units of ethical and cultural
progress", whose improvement in enhancing professional ethics and
boycotting "paid news" will be open to public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 journalists attended today's conference, which
was participated in by 30 different sites across the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
