<HEADLINE> Earthquake Victims in Xinjiang Busy with Rescue, Relief Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, January 23 (Xinhua) -- A group of ranking officials
have gone to the earthquake-hit area in northwest China to
organize rescue and disaster-relief work.
</P>
<P>
An earthquake measuring 6.4 on the Richter Scale rocked Jiashi
County in Kashgar, in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region on
January 21, killing 12 people, injuring 36, and causing a great
deal of property damage.
</P>
<P>
The officials expressed the concern of the central government
and Party organizations for those who lost family members in the
disaster.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of tents have reportedly been set up, and more than
1,000 soldiers of the People's Liberation Army are making an
effort to conduct rescue work, and to keep people calm.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that some 50 trucks of coal are on their way to
the area to help local people deal with the cold.
</P>
<P>
The Kashgar branch of the China People's Insurance Company has
paid in advance one million yuan to the seriously-damaged county
in compensation.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, local public health departments are reportedly busy
with rescue and relief work and post and telecommunications
departments are restoring service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
