<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Seamen End Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Greek seamen and dock workers
today ended a 10-day strike after intensive all-night negotiations
between the government and the Panhellenic Seamen's Federation
(PNO).
</P>
<P>
The stoppage, which paralyzed transport and caused hardships to
the Greek islands, involved all ships with Greek crews and kept
vessels moored at port stranding thousands of angry passengers and
hundreds of local and foreign lorries in Greek and Italian ports.
</P>
<P>
A federation spokesman said their union has accepted "improved
government proposals submitted to them by a committee headed by
Merchant Marine Minister Stavros Soumakis".
</P>
<P>
The seamen's main demands was preservation of a special tax
status for them since 1955 which the government changed in its tax
legislation.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman warned that "if satisfactory solutions will not
be given there will be a new round of strikes."
</P>
<P>
The government's new proposals include the starting of a
dialogue between the employers, the seamen and the state for the
settlement of employment issues on ocean-going vessels, the
seamen's registry, preservation of pensions at 58 percent of their
basic wages and the taxation of officers' salaries with 8 percent
this year, 9 percent from 1998 and on, and 4 and 6 percent
respectively for lower-ranking crews. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
