<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC Backtracks on EU Expansion Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC)
today backtracked on its earlier prediction on the timing of
expansion of the European Union by saying that no date for EU
enlargement could be forecast beyond the start of negotiations,
scheduled for early 1998.
</P>
<P>
This statement came after the Commission released a fact sheet
in which it predicted that no new country was likely to join the
15-member bloc before the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
It called the release of the statement "erroneous" and
"regrettable."
</P>
<P>
"The European Commission hopes that the first accession can be
realized as soon as possible," it said in the statement, pointing
out that this position, shared by Commission President Jacques
Santer and other members of the Commission, remained "unchanged"
at present.
</P>
<P>
It reiterated that the eventual date of accession depends on
the following factors: the state of preparation of the candidate
countries as well as of the EU itself, especially in the context
of the Inter-Governmental Conference currently underway to decide
on reforms to and the future shape of the EU, the duration of
accession talks as well as ratification procedures.
</P>
<P>
In a 30-point fact sheet on the EU's enlargement process
released on Wednesday, the Commission said: "Taking into account
the possible duration of negotiations and time needed for
ratification, the earliest realistic date for the first accessions
is likely to be no earlier than 2002."
</P>
<P>
This prediction has sparked concern across Eastern Europe,
especially in Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary, who are seen
as the most likely to be the first applicant countries to obtain
EU membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
