<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Says PC Legal Panel Recommendation Is Right </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) Tung Chee Hwa said
today that the latest recommendation of the Preparatory
Committee's Legal sub-group on the amendments to some Hong Kong
laws is right.
</P>
<P>
Tung delivered a speech this evening when accepting the Award
of "1996 Leader of the Year".
</P>
<P>
Tung said that the Preparatory Committee's Legal sub-group
recently recommended certain laws either in part or in total to
cease to be in force after July 1 this year, which is a follow-up
of the work of the Preliminary Working Committee.
</P>
<P>
"These are not new issues," he said. The latest recommendation
is "a follow-up of the work of the Preliminary Working Committee"
and "is in fact more open."
</P>
<P>
He said the Preliminary Working Committee and the Preparatory
Committee's Legal Sub-group actually looked at 624 laws and more
than a thousand sub-laws. Ultimately, the Legal sub-group decided
to recommend to the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress that 15 laws in their entirety and 11 laws in part shall
cease to be in force because they are inconsistent with the Basic
Law.
</P>
<P>
Most of these changes are recommended because of the colonial
aspect of the laws which shall cease to apply after July 1, 1997.
Three of them are electoral laws which for reasons well known to
everyone shall cease to be in force. There are three changes that
deal with the Bill of Rights, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said some people in Hong Kong have alleged that there are
wholesale changes of Hong Kong laws proposed by the Preparatory
Committee Legal sub-group. But in fact, the changes are minimal,
so these allegations are far from being the truth, Tung pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
"With regards to the Bill of Rights, let me further state,
there is no need for anxiety because Hong Kong people's freedom
and rights are guaranteed by Chapter 3 of the Basic Law," Tung
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the amendments to the Bill of Rights are legalistic and
technical in nature and is not controversial.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the recommendation that the Public Order
Ordinance and the Societies Ordinance should cease to be in force,
Tung said it is important to get the right balance between
individual rights and social order for the good of the entire
community.
</P>
<P>
"The issue is not about the freedom of expression and freedom
of assembly. The issue is not about human rights," he said. "The
issue here is really getting it right between balancing individual
rights and the good of the public at large."
</P>
<P>
"My personal view on the Societies Ordinance is also similar to
that of the Legal sub-group," he said. "I believe the Preparatory
Committee Legal sub-group's recommendation is right because I do
not believe the community wants undue foreign political influences
in Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
He said it is understandable that these issues have created
feelings of concern in some areas of the community.
</P>
<P>
"I know many skeptics will not be turned into believers by my
words. To those people, I urge you to have faith. To these
non-believers, I also invite you to come and look for yourselves
after July 1, 1997 to see how strong, how vibrant, how cohesive
and how free we are as a society," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
