<HEADLINE> Canada to Ban Mammal Additives in Cattle Feed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Canada is expected to enact
regulations soon to ban the use of mammal additives in cattle feed
in a bid to reduce mad-cow disease risk.
</P>
<P>
At present, additives, namely ground-up bits of other cows,
sheep or any other mammal, can make up 20 percent or more of
cattle feed in Canada.
</P>
<P>
The ban is in response to the human health risks associated
with eating meat from cows infected with bovine spongiform
encephalopathy or BSE, a fatal brain condition commonly known as
mad-cow disease, according to today's Globe and Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
A decade of research in Britain has linked cattle feed
containing ground bone and body parts from sheep with the
appearance of brain-wasting BSE in cows in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
British scientists announced last year that they had strong
evidence of a long-suspected link between BSE and some cases of
its human counterpart, Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease.
</P>
<P>
Since last April, Canada has been considering a ban on the
animal-feed additives. The ban could come into effect as early as
April 1 of this year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The most likely substitute for meat products in cattle feed
would be soya, although fish and poultry could theoretically be
used.
</P>
<P>
The cost of transformation to a vegetarian diet for naturally
vegetarian animals might cost Canada as high as 22 million U.S.
dollars, according to an official at the Agriculture and Agrifood
Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
