<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Real Agricultural Prices 1.2 Percent Down in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Real agricultural producer
prices in the European Union(EU) are expected to be 1.2 percent
down in 1996 compared with 1995, according to a report today from
the EU's statistical office Eurostat.
</P>
<P>
Eurostat commented that steep price falls for calves and cattle
were thought to reflect consumer fears of mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
Today's forecast followed rises of 0.3 percent in both 1995 and
1994. Real prices fell steeply from 1989 to 1993, then stabilized.
These latest data showed a cumulative decline of 16.1 since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Last year only Italy(1.6 percent) and the Netherlands(0.2
percent) registered increases.
</P>
<P>
Biggest decrease was Finland's steep 15.0 percent, partly due
to phasing out national price subsidies.
</P>
<P>
Other notable falls were returned by Luxembourg(7.2 percent),
Ireland(5.3 percent), Sweden(5.0 percent) and Britain(4.2
percent).
</P>
<P>
Real prices for crop products are expected to be 1.1 percent
down following the rise of 4.8 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Real prices for animals and animal products fell by 1.3
percent, less than the 3.8 percent decline in 1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
