<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Method Invented in Greece for Cleaning Oil Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 23 (Xinhua) -- A Greek research professor today
presented a new method for cleaning up oil pollution in the sea
which uses magnetism to separate the oil from sea water.
</P>
<P>
"Clean Mag" is a special compound of plastic materials
containing magnetized particles.
</P>
<P>
Professor George Nicolaides said the compound had the property
of being able to selectively absorb petroleum products and oils
without absorbing water.
</P>
<P>
"This means that when the petroleum products come into contact
with the compound, they quickly stick to Clean Mag and remain on
the surface of the sea where they can easily be collected with the
use of electromagnets," Nicolaides said.
</P>
<P>
According to the professor, present methods of cleaning up oil
slicks are extremely costly and are never completely efficient.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, he stressed, Clean Mag has a 100 percent pollution
retrieval rate, is low cost and can be recycled.
</P>
<P>
Nicolaides said that when Clean Mag went into mass production,
he expected great interest on the part of shipping companies and
foreign countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
