<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notebook: New Bangkok Airport: To Be or Not To Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh seemed to have stirred up a nest of hornets when he
proposed that the second Bangkok international airport be shelved
because of its high cost.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all newspapers in the country today gave front-page or
multi-page prominence to the controversial postponement,
presenting the pros and cons of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
 AN APPLE OF DISCORD
</P>
<P>
In fact, at Tuesday's cabinet meeting no decision was made on
the fate of the new airport at Nong Ngu Hao. Ministers, except
those from the Social Action Party, simply went along with the
prime minister when he made the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit, in keeping his election campaign promise to revive
the economy, said the existing Bangkok Don Muang international
airport could be expanded to cope with the increasing passenger
volume over the next 10 years by requesting the air force, which
has a base adjacent to the civil airport, to provide space for the
expansion.
</P>
<P>
According to the prime minister, the expansion is expected to
cost only 10 billion baht (400 million US dollars), while the
first phase alone of the Nong Ngu Hao airport would cost nearly
100 billion baht (four billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Chavalit indicated at the meeting that he wanted the
37-year-old project delayed for at least 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Nong Ngu Hao, which means the Cobra Swamp, is low-lying and
flood-prone, and needs land refill with sand and construction of a
six-km-long flood prevention wall.
</P>
<P>
 ACCUSATION
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Montri Pongpanich, leader of the Social
Action Party, is among those who are most strongly against the
postponement of the new airport project.
</P>
<P>
In the division of work of the six-party coalition government,
his party is in charge of the project, with Somsak Thepsuthin, a
deputy transport and communications minister, overseeing the
construction. Recently Somsak approved a landfill contract worth
10 billion baht (400 million dollars), which Deputy Prime Minister
Amnuay Virawan considered too high.
</P>
<P>
Unhappy with the shelving, Montri claimed that a certain
neighboring country has bribed a senior Thai politician to
sabotage the new airport. He did not produce evidence or specify
names to substantiate his claim.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the new airport, when completed, could
rival major international airports in the region, such as
Singapore's Changi.
</P>
<P>
Judging from the vengeance with which Montri has come back, the
prime minister's proposal could well become an apple of discord
leading to inter-party conflict in the coalition government.
</P>
<P>
AMNUAY WANTS MORE
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the air force does not seem to be willing to
offer
all the help the prime minister wants.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Amnuay, a staunch supporter for
Chavalit's idea,
said that it would be the best if the air force headquarters would
move
out and give up nearly all of its 385 hectares of land for the
expansion
of the existing airport.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the request, Air Force Commander-in-Chief Amorn
Naewmalee said on Wednesday that the air force is ready to
relocate only
some of its units and make only 100 hectares of land available for
the
civil airport expansion project, falling far short of Amnuay's
expectations.
</P>
<P>
 TO ABORT OR TO KEEP, WHICH IS MORE COSTLY
</P>
<P>
The government's proposed shelving of the Nong Ngu Hao airport
project
may have an impact on 42 companies and one education institute
which have
been contracted to study the design and other work including site
improvements.
</P>
<P>
The total value of these signed contracts is 13.33 billion baht
(533.2
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
At least seven billion baht (280 million dollars) has been paid
during the past few decades since the project was conceived 37
years ago. The payout includes 1.44 billion baht (57.6 million
dollars) in compensation for relocation of villagers.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the flood wall has begun and temporary roads
inside
the site are also being built.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that dusting up the project after 10 years would
cause
the overall cost to skyrocket.
</P>
<P>
Among factors leading to much higher cost are more expensive
labor,
materials and design. Besides, those farmers who have left the
site after
receiving compensation will return to resume their fish-farming.
</P>
<P>
Lost opportunity of the new airport is even more incalculable.
</P>
<P>
The cost of winding up Nong Ngu Hao will be high. it could be
almost
as high as going ahead and building the airport, a local newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
In the weeks to come, the government will have a hard time
making a
decision on the project.  
</P>
</TEXT>
