<HEADLINE> Telecoms Liberalization Positive Impact on Employment: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Up to 1.3 million jobs might
be created or maintained by 2005 in the European Union(EU) in a
scenario of rapid liberalization of the telecommunications sector,
according to a recent study of the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
While traditional telecom operators could stand to lose up to
286,000 jobs, the study indicated that this would be compensated
by job creation in the telecom sector as a whole.
</P>
<P>
It said new operators could lead to a net creation or
maintenance of up to 93,000 jobs for the whole sector.
</P>
<P>
This independent study, carried out by French consultants BIPE
Conseil on behalf of the European Commission, is one of many
elements feeding into the debate on the social and employment
aspects of information society launched by the Commission.
</P>
<P>
However, EU Social Affairs Commissioner Padraig Flynn did not
show much optimism, commenting on the study that "forecasts provide
some indications as to future developments, but by their very
nature are uncertain."
</P>
<P>
With a few exceptions, 1 January 1998 is the deadline for full
liberalization of EU's telecommunications market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
