<HEADLINE> U.S. Studies More Cuts in Nuclear Warheads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
studying the possibility of a new agreement with Russia on further
cuts in strategic nuclear weapons based on the 1993 accord which
sets to reduce some 50 percent of such weapons, U.S. senior
officials revealed.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Defense Department is secretly studying the military
consequences of an additional cut of 1, 000 to 1,500 nuclear
warheads to leave residual forces of as few as 2,000 weapons, a
Washington Post report said today.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials see that a proposal for new cuts as a way to
persuade Russian legislators to ratify the so-called START II
treaty, which calls for the 50 percent cuts in nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The START II was signed in January 1993 by Yeltsin and
President George Bush, was approved by the U.S. Congress a year
ago, but the Russian parliament has yet voted on it as many
Russian legislators were upset by the NATO's plan to expand
eastern-word to include some of the former Warsaw Pact member
nations.
</P>
<P>
Moscow has also been balking at the accord on grounds that it
will cost too much to implement and will impel the Russian
government to build additional strategic weapons to maintain rough
parity with the United States at the ceiling the treaty sets.
</P>
<P>
The study is being conducted by the Joint Chiefs of staff and
by civilian experts at the Pentagon as a part of a broader review
of military strategy and budgets, the Post said. It is also a
preparation for the scheduled summit meeting between U.S.
President Bill Clinton and his Russian counterpart Boris Yeltsin
in March.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has said that he would support setting a lower ceiling
for strategic nuclear weapons of the two countries than the one
set by START II.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials also suggest Clinton to reach a tentative accord
on the framework of a new treaty during the summit, the newspaper
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
