<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Diamond Prices Plummet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Auridiam Zimbabwe, a diamond
mining firm, said here today diamond prices plunged by nearly 40
percent following a decision by some major producing countries to
sever links with the mineral's international marketing agency.
</P>
<P>
Kevin Dabinett, general manager of the company, said the major
producing countries such as Russia and Australia are no longer
willing to sell their diamond through the Central Selling
Organisation (CSO), which exerted downward pressure on the
mineral's price in the international market.
</P>
<P>
He noted that such moves by the key producers had negatively
affected smaller producers like Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"This has forced diamond prices down and in fact current
prices are 40 percent lower than when we first started," said the
general manager.
</P>
<P>
The agreement between Russia and the CSO expired a few years
ago and the Russians have not expressed willingness to renew the
agreement while Argyle, the largest Australian Producer, has also
refuse to sell to the organisation.
</P>
<P>
Russia, Australia, South Africa and Botswana are among the top
diamond producing countries while Zimbabwe contributes only a
negligible amount to total world production.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Dabinett said the company anticipated that diamond
production at its River Banch Mine near Beitbridge of South
Zimbabwe would increase by over six percent to 500,000 carats
this year, following last year's 470,000 carats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
