<HEADLINE> Greek PM, U.S. Ambassador Meet in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis today had a one-hour meeting with U.S. ambassador to
Athens, Thomas Niles, which according to informed sources covered
the entire spectrum of Greek-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that Greek-Turkish relations and the Cyprus
problem had also been discussed in the light of recent
developments.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greece's Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos today
called on the United States to commit itself to guaranteeing the
implementation of an agreement to ban military flights over the
divided island of Cyprus "whatever may happen".
</P>
<P>
Pangalos was commenting on recent statements by U.S. State
Department spokesman Nicholas Burns that Cyprus was in no need of
Russian made S-300 missiles if there was a moratorium on military
overflights over Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The Americans first put forward the proposal to ban military
flights over Cyprus by Greek and Turkish aircraft in July 1996 and
revived it recently after Cyprus decided to buy anti-aircraft
missiles.
</P>
<P>
Pangalos said Greece had laid out very specific proposals both
on the demilitarization of Cyprus and the creation of good
neighbourly relations with Turkey. "We have done our duty. It's
time for Turkey to do its", the Minister added.
</P>
<P>
He also said Greece was ready to contribute to any development
which will defuse tension in the Aegean, clarifying however that
his country was not prepared to negotiate over its sovereign
rights. 
</P>
