<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irish Government Unveils 1997-1998 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The Irish government unveiled
the country's 1997-1998 budget on Wednesday, mixing tax cuts with
modest public spending rises, while keeping on track to qualify
for membership of the European Monetary Union.
</P>
<P>
Irish Finance Minister Ruairi Quinn said that current public
expenditure was expected to increase by 6 percent over last year's
13.4 billion Irish pounds (about 21 billion U.S. dollars), according
to press reports from Dublin.
</P>
<P>
Standard rate of income tax is cut by one percentage point to
26 percent, while personal allowances have been raised by 250
Irish pounds (about 400 dollars) for a single person, and by 500
Irish pounds (about 800 dollars) to married couples.
</P>
<P>
The Irish government is also planning to commit 525 million
Irish pounds (about 840 million dollars) over the next three years
to boost weekly welfare payments, child benefit and family income
supplement.
</P>
<P>
Quinn stressed that the aim of the government was to "reward
work, promote enterprise and strengthen social security".
</P>
<P>
"For the first time in our modern history we are seeing a
sustained net increase in jobs, net emigration was stopped and
some people are coming home," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
