<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qatar to Increase Oil, Condensate Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Qatar, one of the major oil
exporters in the world, has planned to increase its crude and
condensate output by 58.2 percent by the year 2000, said reports
reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Qatar, a member of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC), plans to produce 710,000 barrels per day (bpd)
of crude and around 200,000 bpd of condensates by 2000, the
reports quoted official sources of the Qatari Ministry of Energy
and Industry as saying in the Qatari capital of Doha Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Qatar now produces over 500,000 bpd of oil and around 75,000
bpd of condensates.
</P>
<P>
The increase would come from new oil fields, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, Qatar has put two new fields on stream
and rejuvenated an aging field under production sharing
agreements with foreign firms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
