<HEADLINE> Ireland to Decide on Participation of Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The Irish government is expected
to make a final decision on whether to participate in the NATO-led
peacekeeping force in former Yugoslavia over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Irish armed forces are making contingency plans to send
troops to Bosnia in an effort to help implement the Bosnia peace
agreement, the Irish Times newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Irish defense sources have indicated that a small contingent of
company (from 80 to 120 troops) was the most they could contribute
to the Stability Force.
</P>
<P>
This could consist of a transport company to distribute
supplies among the 30,000-strong NATO-led force or a specialist
company of engineers or demining experts, they said.
</P>
<P>
The smallest contribution would be a platoon-sized contingent
of around 30 military policemen for security duties, they added.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Irish Foreign Affairs Department was quoted
as saying on Wednesday that the matter was being looked at and
would be dealt with "without too much delay."
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that Ireland made a considerable
contribution to the peace-keeping operations last year when the
Irish government held the six-month European Union (EU)
presidency. 
</P>
