<HEADLINE> SADC Parliamentarians Urged to Develop Common </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(By Pei Shanqin)
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The Southern Africa
Development Community (SADC) parliamentarians were urged today to
develop and nurture a common vision and a common regional
perspective on a larger and wider regional context.
</P>
<P>
Opening a two-day interim plenary assembly of the SADC
parliamentary forum here today, President Benjamin Mkapa said
that the SADC will be in a position to make southern Africa a
significant player in the emerging globalizing investment and
trade regime.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said the investment and trade in SADC countries should
accrue to all SADC member countries on the basis of balance,
equity and mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
"Our region is blessed with enormous natural resources, if
used properly, they can make our countries rich," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president added, "with vision, determination, courage and
political will we can make a change in the lives of our people
and be a force in our own right in the liberalized global village
of the next century."
</P>
<P>
He said the agreement on the establishment of the forum is an
expression of the firm commitment to democracy, transparency,
good governance and the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
However, the president said that the forum will speed up the
development of a new political culture in the region which will
be a beacon of light, an inspiration, to the rest of the
continent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Tanzanian president said that unity should be
the cornerstone for the integration of the SADC if past mistakes made
elsewhere in Africa are to be avoided.
</P>
<P>
The SADC parliamentary forum, attended by about 50 delegates
from its 12 member states, is expected to adopt its constitution
and elect office bearers.
</P>
<P>
The SADC groups Tanzania, Zambia, Malawi, Mozambique,
Zimbabwe, Botswana, Angola, Namibia, South Africa, Lesotho,
Swaziland and Mauritius. 
</P>
