<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EMU "Very Unlikely" to Start on Time, Major </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John
Major told parliament today the cabinet concluded that it was
"very unlikely" Britain would join a single currency in January
1999.
</P>
<P>
"It is very unlikely, though not impossible, that the single
currency itself could proceed safely on January 1, 1999," Major
told Commons. "But if it did proceed without reliable convergence
we would not, of course, be part of it."
</P>
<P>
His statement came after a 90-minute cabinet meeting to discuss
Britain's approach to European Economic and Monetary Union (EMU),
the main part of which is the single currency.
</P>
<P>
Kenneth Clarke, the Chancellor of the Exchequer, told reporters
as he left Downing Street: "It is unlikely in my opinion we would
start EMU on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"We were proceeding on the basis of the policy that we're going
to negotiate and decide at the right time, and that was accepted
by everybody."
</P>
<P>
Foreign Secretary Malcolm Refkind also said: "The crucial
requirement is always the national interest."
</P>
<P>
Major's cabinet is split between ministers who want to rule out
entry into a single currency during the next parliament and those
who want to stick to the policy of keeping Britain's options open.
</P>
<P>
Refkind made it clear earlier he believed neither the national
nor his party's interests would be served by ditching the currency
opt-out Major negotiated in 1991.
</P>
<P>
European Commissioner Leon Brittan who is a strong supporter of
EMU said today the benefits of a single currency would become
clear "when we remove our Eurosceptic blinkers".
</P>
<P>
He also warned the Government against any shift from its "wait
and see" policy on EMU. The warn came after Prime Minister Major
revealed the cabinet considered a 1999 entry into the currency as
"very unlikely".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
