<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Consumer Prices Rise Modestly in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Canadian consumers faced a 2.2
percent rise in the price of goods and services between December
1995 and December 1996.
</P>
<P>
Statistics Canada said today that advances in transportation
charges contribute to a large part of this annual Consumer Price
Index (CPI) increase.
</P>
<P>
Food prices, university tuition fees, telephone charges and
fuel oil prices also climbed in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
December's inflation rate was higher than that of November and
October, which was 2 percent and 1.8 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The acceleration in inflation since September was due mainly to
increases in the rates for auto insurance, gasoline, air fares and
food, Statistics Canada said.
</P>
<P>
Between 1995 and 1996, the all-items CPI for Canada increased
by 1.6 percent, the agency said, which calculated the annual
average index by averaging the indices for the 12 months of the
calendar year.
</P>
<P>
Higher inflation in December is being seen here as another sign
that the Canadian economy is moving.
</P>
<P>
The modest price rise also reduces the chance that the Bank of
Canada would cut interest rates further, analysts here said.
</P>
</TEXT>
