<HEADLINE> European Envoy to Help Restart Israeli-Syrian Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 23 (Xinhua) -- European special envoy
Miguel Angel Moratinos will launch a bid next week to resume the
stalled Israeli-Syrian negotiations, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos, also Spanish Ambassador to Israel, will travel to
Syrian capital Damascus Monday to discuss the Israeli-Syrian
peace track with Syrian leaders. He will try to nudge Israel
and Syria closer in order to resume the stalled peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The European envoy, who had been excluded by the United States
and Israel from meditating the Israeli-Palestinian talks on
Hebron pullback, is now in the best position to get the
Israeli-Syrian track moving, the report said.
</P>
<P>
One reason is that Syria is now angered by a series of moves by
the United States, the latest being its pressuring South Africa to
defer a 650-million-dollar deal on computerizing Syrian tanks'
fire systems, observers noted.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the outgoing U.S. Secretary of State Warren
Christopher recently sent a message to Israel, claiming that the
understanding reached between Israel's previous Labor government
and Syria would not bind the current Likud government, they said.
</P>
<P>
Under the unsigned understanding, the Labor government declared
its willingness to totally withdraw from the Golan Heights,
which Israel seized in 1967 from Syria, in return for sealing a
peace pact with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Following the just-completed Hebron redeployment that helped
ease the tension in the region, Israel is increasing pressure on
Syria to come back to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
However, Syria has rejected repeated calls from Israel for
resuming the peace talks, insisting the negotiations should only
be reconvened on the basis of the understanding that it reached
with the Labor government.
</P>
<P>
The Likud government vowed in its police guidelines never to
relinquish the Golan Heights under excuses of protecting its
northern border and valuable water resources.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Syrian peace talks broke off last March after a series
of Islamic suicide bombing attacks in Israel killed 58
people. Since the hardline Likud government came to power last
June, a military stand-off has been brewing in the border,
fueling rumors about a possible war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
