<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Justice Department
announced today that February 23 would be the deadline for U.S.
citizens to add to the 250 claims seeking compensation from the
German government for Nazi concentration camp survivors.
</P>
<P>
"We are racing against time to compensate them," Attorney
General Janet Reno said of the program unveiled in June.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement between the U.S. and German governments, any
U.S citizen who was interned in a Nazi concentration camp during
World War Two can file a claim for reparation.
</P>
<P>
The department said that 250 claims had been submitted, but
they would be checked with international records.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-German agreement applies to both civilians and
military personnel who were U.S. citizens at the time of their
internment in the Nazi camps. 
