<HEADLINE> Libyan Plane Flies Overseas Despite Embargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Despite the U.N. air flight
embargo on Libya, a Libyan Airlines aircraft has made a
return trip between Libyan capital of Tripoli and Ghanian capital
of Accra, according to reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan news agency said the plane returned to Tripoli today
carrying a delegation of the Libyan Ministry of Foreign Affairs
which had official talks with Ghanian officials in Accra.
</P>
<P>
The report did not specify the route followed by the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Libyan authorities allowed the U.S. balloonist Steve Fosset to
transit its airspace aboard his balloon last Saturday. Then
Tripoli said it considered that the international embargo had been
lifted.
</P>
<P>
Libya also addressed a message to the U.N. Security Council
last week underlining that Tripoli would permit the transit and
landing of any aircraft overflying Libya and its airports, whereas
Libyan planes would resume flights at once to other countries of
the world.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed the air flight embargo on
Libya in April 1992 after Libya refused to hand over two suspects
for blasting a Pan AM flight over Scotland in 1988, leaving 270
people dead.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in April 1994, Libyan pilgrims flew to Saudi Arabia to
perform pilgrimage, and, ever since, the U.N. Security Council had
permitted Egyptian planes to transport Libyan pilgrims to Mecca
in 1994 and 1995, taking off from Libyan airports. 
</P>
