<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia FM Meets With UN Court Chief Prosecutor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Foreign Minister
Milan Milutinovic met today with Chief Prosecutor of the Hague
International Criminal Tribunal Louise Arbour on cooperation
between Yugoslavia and the tribunal.
</P>
<P>
Arbour, accompanied by her deputy Graham Blewitt, is paying a
several-day visit to Belgrade. This is Arbour's first visit to
Yugoslavia after she took over as chief prosecutor of the Hague
tribunal in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
The international war crimes tribunal was established in 1993
in line with a U.N. resolution to investigate and try the war
criminals in the former Yugoslavia. The court has listed 75 war
crime suspects, with only seven under custody and one being
sentenced.
</P>
<P>
Milutinovic and Arbour exchanged views on cooperation in the
sphere of war crimes investigation between Yugoslavia and the
tribunal, the Tanjug news agency quoted a Yugoslav Foreign
Ministry statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed that the opening of the Belgrade liaison
office of the Hague tribunal had added an extra momentum to the
cooperation, it said.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the office in August 1996 made it possible to
establish regular contacts between the Hague tribunal's
prosecution and Yugoslav authorities and non-governmental
organizations.
</P>
<P>
It had greatly facilitated the work of the tribunal's
investigators, including their access to victims of crimes
committed on the territory of the former Yugoslavia and potential
witnesses of those crimes who have found refuge in Yugoslavia, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Minister Milutinovic said he hoped prosecutor Arbour would help
the tribunal perform its duties in an unbiased way, which he noted
would improve the mutual cooperation and confidence, it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
