<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Promises US Dues Payment to UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today promised visiting U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan that he
will work with Congress to pay overdue U.S. dues to the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
"In the weeks ahead, I will be working with Congress to reach
an agreement through which America can pay our arrears to the
U.N., meet our obligations, and continue to spur real progress,"
Clinton said at the White House after meeting Annan.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., which contributes 25 percent of the U.N. regular
budget, owes the world body 1.3 billion U.S. dollars, bringing it
into deep financial trouble.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot expect to lead through the United Nations unless we
are prepared to pay our own money, and to pay what we owe, as they
do what they should along the path of reform," Clinton declared.
</P>
<P>
"As long as the United Nations does its part, we simply have to
be prepared to pay our debts and pay our dues," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before meeting Clinton, Annan said, "I
don't think I should be seen as a beggar." He stressed that he
needs financial support to reform the U.N.
</P>
<P>
"If we do not change, we will lose our relevance," Annan said,
adding, "What the United Nations wants is what the U.S. also
wants: a reformed United Nations."
</P>
<P>
He added, "If they could release the money to us, we could get
on with the work of reform. We can get on with reshaping the U.N."
</P>
<P>
Prior to the meeting with Clinton, Annan met with U.S.
Vice-President Al Gore and the new secretary of state, Madeleine
Albright.
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic mission of the new U.N. chief is seen as a good
sign in relations between the U.N. and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
"I think that is a very good sign of the support that the
United States is going to give to the United Nations," Albright
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 44 House members signed a letter to Clinton, calling
for the fulfillment of the U.S. financial obligation to the U.N.,
or the U.S. will lose influence and further cripple the
organization.
</P>
<P>
Annan, on his first trip to Washington as the U.N.
secretary-general, is trying to convince the U.S. congressmen to
agree on paying U.S. dues to the U.N.
</P>
<P>
He said that he is "fairly certain" that in time the Congress
and the U.S. government will pay the debts. However, he stressed
that he is not sure when they will do it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
