<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Zoologists Save Vultures from Extinction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Bird-lovers northern Israel
nowadays is surprised to see the vultures back in the nature
after 45 years of disappearance.
</P>
<P>
This is the result of an urgent rescue project carried out by
zoology Professor Amos Ar and his assistant Ohad Hatzofe in the
Tel Aviv University.
</P>
<P>
Through artificial hatchery, they have succeeded in increasing
the number of vultures which are otherwise facing extinction
because of low fertility rate and the environment disturbance.
</P>
<P>
Supported by the Rothschild Foundation and Society for
Protection of Nature in Israel, Ar and Hatzofe have conducted
basic researches on vultures about their embryo's metabolism and
eco-physiology, which were implemented in the hatching project.
</P>
<P>
The vultures reach sexual maturity between the ages of four
and six years. They are monogamous, and the females lay only one
egg a year. The couple court, build nests, and mate between
November and January, then incubate their egg until March. If
the egg hatches, the chick remains in the nest for about 110
days and even afterwards is fed by its parents.
</P>
<P>
Because of the heavy parental investment in a single chick,
any interference with nesting or harm to the egg may cause the
loss of a whole year and helicopter training near the breeding
colony in northern Israel has caused adult vultures to abandon
their nests.
</P>
<P>
Professor Ar collected vulture eggs from the wild and the zoo
to transfer to his hatching house. In order to increase the
hatching rate, he learned to pierce the shells with tiny needle
holes to rise the moisture.
</P>
<P>
Once hatched and weighing some 170 grams, the chicks are
adopted by vulture couples selected from the university's
zoological park. Using transmitters, the scientists identify and
follow the vultures after they are freed back into the
wild. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
