<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regulations to Stop People in Debt Out of China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- China's State Administration of
Taxation and the Ministry of Public Security recently passed a
rule that is designed to stop tax cheats from leaving China.
</P>
<P>
Sources say that the move is intended to reduce loss of tax
revenues and to protect the country's interests.
</P>
<P>
With growing contacts between China and foreign countries, more
foreigners are doing business in China, and the country has seen
rapid growth in the number of foreign workers over recent years.
</P>
<P>
It became necessary, therefore, to have regulations control the
entry and exit of foreigners, authorities say, and ones that allow
tax bureaus to delay the departure of people who want to leave
without paying taxes or failing to provide a tax guarantor.
</P>
<P>
The bureaus can ask public security departments to stop people
who insist on leaving, the rule says, and that those concerned can
leave as soon as they pay all the back taxes, or provide a tax
guarantor.
</P>
<P>
Those who declare bankruptcy and have gone through the
necessary procedures in accordance with Chinese law, can leave
China.
</P>
<P>
If a legal person is behind in taxes, the legal representative
is prohibited from leaving, according to the rule.
</P>
<P>
In case there is change in the legal person or person in
charge, that person or persons will be stopped from leaving China
and, if the legal person is outside the country, the principal
leading person will be held responsible and forbidden from exiting
the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao to Step Up Localization of Law: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Macao Governor Vasco Rocha Vieira
pledged to step up the localization process of law and the legal
structure in Macao to "prepare for the future after the handover
of power."
</P>
<P>
The governor made these remarks on Thursday at an annual legal
meeting, which was attended by leading legal officials of the
government.
</P>
<P>
"The joint declaration signed by China and Portugal 10 years
ago means a guarantee for the future stability and prosperity of
Macao," he said in an address at the meeting. "The government will
make great efforts to fulfill the duty laid down in the joint
declaration to ensure that the Macao Special Administrative Region
will enjoy autonomy."
</P>
<P>
The governor said that as there is less than three years left
for the handover of Macao, it is urgent to localize the law and
the legal structure.
</P>
<P>
The priority is the training of personnel, he said, adding that
more local law officials, lawyers and court clerks will take
office this year and in 1998, following the first three local law
officials who assumed office last year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the overall legal structure currently in operation
will be localized so that it will stride over 1999.
</P>
<P>
General principles will be worked out to define the formation
and rights of the court of last resort and the court of second
instance, the duty of legal officials and the formation and rights
of bodies governing legal officials.
</P>
<P>
Vieira said that the court of first instance will be
restructured this year and that major laws including the civil
law, the business law and the law on civil procedure will be
prepared as well.
</P>
<P>
Two other leading localized laws -- the criminal code and the
law of criminal procedures -- were promulgated earlier.
</P>
<P>
"It will be a top priority of this year's work of the
government to continue the localization of law, so that Macao will
have modernized and future-oriented laws," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
