<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Tap More Foreign Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines will open more
potentially big markets in 1997 for its export products as part of
its efforts to attain a 50 billion U.S. dollars export target by
the year 2000, the Department of Trade and Industry (DOTI) said
today.
</P>
<P>
While continuing to tap its traditional foreign markets, Trade
and Industry Secretary Cesar Bautista said the country will try to
increase its exports to East Europe, South America, South Africa
and India.
</P>
<P>
The country's traditional markets include East Asia, West
Europe, the Association of Southeast Asian Nations and the North
America Free Trade Area, which groups Canada, Mexico and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
These markets, of which the United States and Japan are the
Philippines' top two trading partners, account for 93 percent of
the country's total exports in 1996, according to Bautista.
</P>
<P>
Bautista said the country's trade deficit reached about 12
billion dollars in 1996, despite an 18 percent increase in the
exports, which outpaced the growth rate of imports for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
He said the country's trade deficit would be wiped out in the
next 10 years only if the growth rate of its exports continued to
outpace the growth rate of its imports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
