<HEADLINE> China To Further Cooperation with UNESCO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- China will continue its
cooperation with the United Nations Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization (UNESCO) to serve the developing countries
in the fields of education, science and culture.
</P>
<P>
Wei Yu, director of the the Chinese National Commission for
UNESCO, promised China's support to UNESCO at an annual meeting
which opened in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
She promised the smooth undertaking of cooperative projects by
China and UNESCO while applying for more cooperation programs.
</P>
<P>
Wei, who is also the vice-minister of the State Education
Commission, viewed China's cooperation with UNESCO in the past
year as "fruitful" and "further improved."
</P>
<P>
She said that two events in 1996 exerted a positive impact on
UNESCO: Chinese President Jiang Zemin accepted UNESCO's invitation
to be a member of the World Solar Commission; And State Councillor
Luo Gan attended the World Solar Summit held in Harare, Zimbabwe,
on behalf of Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
The 30th International Geological Congress, the 62nd General
Conference of the International Federation of Library
Associations, and the 13th International Congress on Archives, all
supported by UNESCO, were respectively held in China.
</P>
<P>
The international conferences promoted the development of
relevant subjects in China, as well as enlarging China's influence
in international scientific circles.
</P>
<P>
China was also actively involved in UNESCO's activities, such
as national education in heavily populated countries, oceanology,
the "Man and Biosphere Project", informatics plan, and hydrologic
plan.
</P>
<P>
Wei said that China and UNESCO started some very meaningful
projects last year about movies, TV programs, radio broadcasting,
fashion design, cultural and natural heritage protection, and
non-material heritage protection. Such projects have helped
promote Chinese culture and increased cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
