<HEADLINE> Dollar Tops 120 Yen in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar continued its
rise in Tokyo today to hit a new 47-month high of 120.20 yen after
official comments that the weakening yen would have a favorable
impact on the Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
The dollar ended the day at 119.94-97 yen at 5 p.m., up from
118.70-75 yen at 9 a.m., having hit an intraday low of 118.32 yen.
</P>
<P>
A senior Bank of Japan economist, commenting on the central
bank's quarterly report on economic prospects, said the yen's
recent weakening trend had affected the Japanese economy favorably.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the market was likely to remain nervous ahead of
the meeting of the Group of Seven industrialized nations on
February 8 in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
Top government spokesman Seiroku Kajiyama said today the yen
seemed to have reached its lower limit and that political and
business circles in Japan and the United States apparently
believed the dollar's range of around 110 to 120 yen is tolerable.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, stock prices fell sharply on a
steep decline on Wall Street overnight.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the market's
First Section closed at 17,689.36, dropping 220.10 points from
Thursday's close.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index, covering all issues
on the First Section, was down 16.27 points to 1,353.48. 
</P>
</TEXT>
