<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Massive Anti-measles Drive Launched in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- A massive anti-measles
immunization drive has been launched in Manila after the
contagious disease has killed 16 children in Manila and its nearby
provinces since January 1, Health Secretary Carmencita Reodica
said today.
</P>
<P>
Reodica said the move was taken as the number of
measles-stricken children admitted into the San Lazaro Hospital
(SLH), the main state-run infectious disease hospital in Manila,
continued to surge this week.
</P>
<P>
She said more places in Metro Manila were placed under close
watch this week after seven more children, all under five years
old, were claimed by the disease.
</P>
<P>
She said that health personnel were directed to find active
measles cases house by house so as to detect the disease early to
prevent complications that usually cause death.
</P>
<P>
Under the massive anti-measles drive, Reodica said all children
below five years old will be immunized. Normally, only children
aged nine to 12 months old are given anti-measles vaccines because
this group is the most vulnerable to contract the disease.
</P>
<P>
So far, 592 measles-infected children have been admitted into
the SLH and the death toll from the disease has risen to 16 as two
more infants, aged one year and six months respectively, died
early this morning.
</P>
<P>
According to Redocia, most of the cases and deaths were
children aged one to four years old. About 82 percent of the
victims were not vaccinated.
</P>
<P>
Despite the high number of measles cases and deaths, Reodica
explained that there is still no basis to declare an outbreak or
epidemic because there is no clustering or concentration of cases
in one specific area.
</P>
<P>
The cases come from different areas of Metro Manila and its
nearby provinces of Bulacan, Cavite and Rizal, she stressed.
</P>
<P>
Measles, transmitted through nose and throat discharges, is a
highly contagious viral disease affecting mostly children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
