<HEADLINE> Lebanon Rejects Israel's Charge against Resistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Beirut announced today that
it has filed an objection to the United Nations over an
Israeli letter to Secretary General Kofi Annan that referred
to resistance attacks against Israel's occupation forces as
"terrorist operations."
</P>
<P>
The official Lebanese National News Agency said that Samir
Mubarak, Lebanese permanent representative at the U.N., has
delivered a letter to Annan objecting to the January 2
Israeli message.
</P>
<P>
"What Israel is calling terrorist operations are resistance
activities targeting Israeli occupation forces, which are taking
place on the Lebanese land," the state-run LNNA quoted the
Lebanese letter as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government reiterated its readiness to ensure
security and legal sovereignty in south Lebanon after the
Jewish state pulls its forces out of the area in accordance
to U.N. Security Council Resolution 425, which calls for an
unconditional Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"The resistance is a term of legitmate right of self-defense
which is stipulated in international documents, and which is
aimed at liberating national lands from foreign occupation,"
Beirut said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
It blamed Israel for problems in south Lebanon, saying "the
Israeli occupation is the main reason for the continued
tension in the area which has caused many human tragedies as
well as destruction and suffering to Lebanese civilians."
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli political and security logic has proved its
failure in securing peace and security in the region and on
each side of the border," the letter added.
</P>
<P>
It underlined that "implementing resolutions passed by the
international community is the only way to security peace and
stability to the people of the Middle east."
</P>
<P>
Hit-and-run attacks by Lebanese guerrillas against the Israeli
occupation forces and its client militia and retaliatory
bombardments constitute a daily scene on the last active
battlefront of the Arab-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
Israel turned the 1,100-square-kilometer occupied border strip
in south Lebanon into its "security zone" in 1985 to protect
its northern border from guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, some 185 Israeli soldiers and more than 800
others have been killed by Lebanese Moslem guerrillas in the
area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
