<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ideal Winter Habitat for Cranes In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,000 red-crowned
cranes have migrated to a beach area of Sheyang County in northern
Jiangsu Province on China's east coast to spend the winter.
</P>
<P>
The beach is a state-level natural reserve for rare and
precious birds and provides an ideal habitat for the red-crowned
crane.
</P>
<P>
The cranes lead a fairly comfortable life there, foraging for
food, strolling about leisurely on the beach, and flying about
occasionally to stretch their wings.
</P>
<P>
In order to protect the rare fowl, the local government has set
up a police post near the zone, to enforce the ban on logging,
cutting down the reeds, and hunting animals.
</P>
<P>
In winter, some departments have also spent tens of thousands
of yuan on irrigating the marshland to make certain that the
red-crowned cranes get ample fish and shrimp, a staple part of
their diet.
</P>
<P>
The favorable environment has caused more red-crowned cranes to
come to spend the winter, and this year, some 1,020 have been
reported, compared to 775 last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
