<HEADLINE> China's Shipbuilding Industry Grows in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- China State Shipbuilding
Corporation (CSSC), completed 1.9 million tons of vessels last
year, hitting a new record.
</P>
<P>
Of the total tonnage, vessels built for overseas clients
accounted for 85 percent, according to sources with CSSC.
</P>
<P>
The delivered vessels include 150,000-ton oil tankers and
50,000-ton bulk carriers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the company's output value from ship repair rose by
21.7 percent last year to reach 1.72 billion yuan, with 70 percent
from overhauling ships of overseas owners.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the company also received orders for building 2.27
million tons of ships, with 1.34 million tons from overseas,
involving a combined contractual value of 25.8 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
New clients from France, Switzerland, and Finland placed orders
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
According to CSSC's blueprint, the corporation expects to
complete three million tons of vessels annually by the year 2000,
thus making China one of the leading shipbuilders in the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
