<HEADLINE> Lebanon Refuses Jordan's Protest over Release of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister
Farez Boueiz stressed here today that a protest raised by
Jordan over Lebanon's decision to release and deport three
Iraqi diplomats were totally unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
At the end of a meeting with Prime Minister Rafik Hariri,
Boueiz confirmed that his government has received a protest
from Jordan, underlining that "neither the contents nor the
form" of the protest was acceptable.
</P>
<P>
Arab diplomatic sources said that relations between Beirut
and Amman soured following the "sharply-worded" protest by
Jordan against Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The three Iraqi diplomats, Ali Sultan Darwish, Mohammed Fares
Kazem and Hadi Hassoun Najim were detained by the Lebanese
authorities after the April 1994 assassination of an Iraqi
opposition leader in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
The slain Iraqi, Taleb Al-Souheil Tamimi, reportedly carried
a Jordanian passport and was a close friend of Jordan's King
Hussein.
</P>
<P>
However, after nearly three years of detention, the Lebanese
Foreign Ministry said last week that the three Iraqis could
not be tried in Lebanon because they enjoyed diplomatic
immunity.
</P>
<P>
On a condition of anonymity, the reliable diplomatic sources
said that the Jordanian protest contained "a very serious
accusation that the release decision was breath of Lebanon's
commitment to combating terrorism."
</P>
<P>
The protest was delivered to Lebanon's ambassador in Amman,
William Habib, by Jordan's Royal Court chief Aoun Khawashneh,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese foreign minister told reporters, "the
international law gives diplomats full and absolute immunity and
no judicial authorities in the world have the right to try
diplomats."
</P>
<P>
"Anyone who believes that he raises the issue in term of
the international law should know and have trust in the
law," the foreign minister added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0087 </DOCNO>
