<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Shipping Industry Welcome Shipping Links Across Straits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong shipowners and port
operators are enthusiastic about the prospect of direct shipping
links between Taiwan and the Chinese mainland, local media
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Port Development Board Secretary Richard Yuen said that of the
total container throughput of 13.3 million TEUs (20-foot
equivalent units) in 1996, only eight percent had been shipped between
the Chinese mainland and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
He said that some of that traffic involved shipments from the
Pearl River Delta area to Taiwan, which would not be much hurt by
direct links with Fujian and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong is the natural catchment for Pearl River Delta
trade, no matter where it is going," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Shipowners' Association chairman George Chao said the
percentage of trade going through Hong Kong would drop but overall
shipment would increase.
</P>
<P>
The shipowners said that any immediate loss in shipping
business would be offset by improved trade on the whole.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Ip Shukwan, secretary for Economic Services, said that
initial estimates were that about one million containers
transshipped through the territory between Taiwan and the mainland
would be affected.
</P>
<P>
The shipping sectors of the Chinese mainland and Taiwan
Wednesday in Hong Kong reached a consensus on technical issues
concerning direct shipping between the selected ports of Fuzhou
and Xiamen on the mainland, and Kaohsiung Port in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong Standard" cited some observers' words as saying that
Hong Kong needed to improve its competitiveness and price if the
territory's port was not to lose out in future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
