<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Foreign Exchange Reserve Figures Published Monthly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Monetary
Authority (HKMA) announced here today that at the end of December
1996, Hong Kong's foreign exchange reserves stood at 63.8 billion
US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents an increase of 15 percent over the
corresponding figure of 1995.
</P>
<P>
An HKMA spokesman said that on this basis, Hong Kong has
maintained its seventh position in the world ranking of foreign
exchange reserve holdings.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, including forward transactions to
be settled, Hong Kong's foreign exchange reserves at the end of
1996 were 69.6 billion US dollars, 22 percent higher than that
recorded at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that these figures do not include Hong
Kong's foreign exchange reserves held in the Land Fund.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the HKMA decided to disclose Hong Kong's
foreign exchange reserve figures monthly rather than quarterly.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Yam, HKMA's chief executive, said that it is part of our
on-going effort to increase transparency in HKMA's operations.
</P>
<P>
HKMA has progressed from annual to half-yearly, quarterly and
now to monthly release of figures on foreign exchange reserves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
