<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan, Saudi Arabia Call on Resumption of Middle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 24 (Xinhua)--Saudi Arabia and Jordan
called on resumption of the Middle East peace process on all
tracks and demanded Israel to respect all its commitments and
agreements to realize just and comprehensive peace in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait News Agency reports from Saudi capital of Riyadh today
said the Saudi King Fahd and Jordanian King Hussein agreed
Thursday night that the Middle East peace talks should rest on
the U.N Security Council resolutions 242, 338 and 425 as well as
Madrid principle of land for peace.
</P>
<P>
The visiting Jordanian king discussed with the Saudi monarch
the recent developments of the Middle East peace process in the
light of the Hebron deal between the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the PNA struck the deal on January 15, ending a
year delay of Israeli troop redeployment from the West Bank city.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, King Hussein elaborated on the efforts he
made to end the stalemate in talks between the PNA and Israel on
Hebron, reports said. During its session last Monday, The Saudi
cabinet welcomed the deal and considered it a step towards
achieving lasting peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
The talks also touched on bilateral relations and ways of
upgrading their level in various fields including economic
cooperation, trade exchanges and employment of Jordanian
workforce in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The talks were attended by Saudi Crown Prince, Deputy Prime
Minister and Chief of the National Guards Prince Abdullah Bin
Abdelaziz, Interior Minister Prince Nayef Bin Abdelaziz, Foreign
Minister Saoud Al-Faisal and other Saudi high ranking officials.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein arrived at Saudi Arabian second holy city of
Al-Madina Thursday morning on his second visit to the Kingdom in
five months for talks with Saudi King Fahd Bin Abdul Aziz and to
pay pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
He was seen off by King Fahd and other Saudi high officials
at the airport late last night.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein visited the Saudi coastal city of Jeddah last
August and held his first meeting with King Fahd since the end
of the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's ties with its largest southern neighbor and other
Gulf Arab states were strained when King Hussein refused to join
Saudi Arabia and other Arab and Western countries in condemning
the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Saudi oil supplies to Jordan were cut off the next month and
Amman was forced to rely solely on Iraq for its energy needs.
</P>
<P>
Things began to improve when King Hussein turned against
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein after the defection of two senior
Iraqi officers to Jordan in 1994 and relations between the two
countries improved dramatically after King Hussein's last visit
to Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of the Gulf War, King Hussein made his first
visit to Saudi Arabia in February, 1994, but he was not received
by Saudi King Fahd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Industrial Base Records Healthy Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Harbin, capital city of
northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, generated 63.7 billion
yuan in gross domestic product (GDP) last year, 13.9 percent more
than in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The output value of three pillar industries -- automobiles,
medicines and electronics -- rose to seven billion yuan last year,
giving a powerful push to the city's overall industrial
development.
</P>
<P>
Harbin, an old industrial base in north China, its economic
development in the past year was characterized by four main
features:
</P>
<P>
-- The accomplished major economic targets were higher than the
national average last year, with goals for industry being
surpassed by 9.3 percent, agriculture by 2.2 percent and service
trades by 4.4 percent;
</P>
<P>
-- There was a coordinated development in agriculture, industry
and tertiary trade;
</P>
<P>
-- Multi-economic sectors developed simultaneously. The
value-added output value of non-state-owned sectors came to 34.9
billion yuan last year, making up more than half of the city's
total GDP;
</P>
<P>
-- Economic growth has embarked on a healthy track, with price
rises lower than the growth of GDP.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exports From Philippines' Subic Bay Soar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' Subic Bay
Freeport shipped out a total of 331 million U.S. dollars' worth of
exports in 1996, an almost 100-percent increase from its 1995
figure of 174 million dollars, according to Trade and Investment
officials.
</P>
<P>
Records of the Subic Bay Metropolitan Authority (SBMA) showed
that the amount of exports by Subic manufacturers exceeded by 31
million dollars the 300 million dollar target which the SBMA set
for 1996.
</P>
<P>
"Subic's exports have taken geometrical increases during the
last three years because of the continuous arrival of foreign
investors lured by the attractiveness of the investment climate in
Subic," SBMA chairman Richard said in a press statement today.
</P>
<P>
Documents also revealed that total exports in 1995 alone, at
174 million dollars, were a 629-percent rise from that of 1994's
24 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year, electronic products accounted for about 76 percent
of the export figures of Subic.
</P>
<P>
Access to the Subic Bay Freeport, which the SBMA sees as the
next Asian transshipment hub, has been eased with the completion
late last year of the 6.8-kilometer Subic-Tipo expressway leading
to the freeport and the opening of the Subic Bay International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
The freeport has already accepted a total of 257 commitments
from investors, bringing the projected investments to some 1.9
billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine, Chinese Cities Seeking Sisterhood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The southern Philippine city of
Iloilo is seeking a sisterhood pact with a coastal city in the
eastern Chinese province of Shangdong, the Philippine News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations for the pact have been underway between officials
from Iloilo, capital of the southern Iloilo province, and Qingdao,
about 500 kilometers southeast of the Chinese capital Beijing, the
news agency said.
</P>
<P>
A delegation of four officials from Qingdao is expected to
finalize the discussions when they visit Iloilo city in late
February, Iloilo city mayor Mansueto Malabor was quoted as saying
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Malabor said Henry Tong, executive director of the Association
for Philippines-China Understanding, had informed him of the
Qingdao municipal government's intention to visit Iloilo for the
purpose.
</P>
<P>
Malabor said he had extended an invitation to the city
officials of Qingdao to visit Iloilo and discuss various aspects
of establishing a city sisterhood pact and other cultural
exchanges that may ensue thereafter.
</P>
<P>
Iloilo has presently a sisterhood treaty with Stockton city in
California and an informal sister pact with Ichon city in South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are four pair of sister cities between China
and the Philippines -- Hangzhou in east China and Baguio in the
northern Philippines; Guangzhou in south China and the Philippine
capital of Manila; Shanghai in east China and Greater Manila; and
Xiamen in southeast China and Cebu in the northern Philippines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
