<HEADLINE> Carl Lewis Finishes Seventh in 100 meters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Carl Lewis of the United
States finished a distance seventh over 100 meters Friday at the
Robin Tait Classic track and field meet in Auckland, New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
In his first outing of the year, the 35-year-old Lewis, who won
the Atlanta Olympics long jump, was easily beaten by fellow
American David Oaks, who won in 10.28 seconds, and a field of
mainly local runners. Lewis wound up 10.76.
</P>
<P>
Lewis, who has a best of 9.86 seconds over 100 meters set in
1991, was unfazed by the loss. He said he wasn't entirely ready
and nor was he expecting to be strongly competitive.
</P>
<P>
``I've been competing for 16 years and so I was relaxed tonight
and I think I'm allowed to do that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
``I will get better as the year goes on, but I don't think I
want to compete as intensely as I have in the past. I've enjoyed
being here and the way this meet has been organized.''
</P>
<P>
Lewis, the owner of nine Olympic gold medals, has twice won the
100-meter gold at the Olympics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
