<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inauguration of Angola's New Government Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The inauguration of Angola's
national unity government, scheduled for January 25, will be
postponed "indefinitely", for which the Angola government blamed
the former rebel UNITA movement.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made public last night by U.N. special
representative Blondin Beye after consulting with the Angolan
government and the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
He said the reason for the delay is that UNITA officials would
not arrive at the capital until February 12, adding that the
opening of the National Assembly, due to be held on January 17,
was also delayed because the UNITA members of parliament did not
reach Luanda as planned.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. mediator noted that the new dates for the
inaugurations cannot be set until all of the UNITA officials and
MPs arrive at the capital.
</P>
<P>
He also pledged that he will hold "intense consultations" with
all sides concerned in the Angolan peace process to decide on the
dates for the inaugurations, especially a post for UNITA leader
Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Angolan government today accused UNITA of
failing to realize the tasks set under the Lusaka peace agreement
as scheduled, thus causing the postponement.
</P>
<P>
However, spokesman for the Angolan government told reporters
that he felt regretted about the delay, but added this does not
mean that the peace process has fallen into dire straits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
