<P>
PARIS, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The French supreme court rejected on Thursday an ultimate
appeal for reexamination of his case by Maurice Papon, who will be
summoned to the investigation court of Bordeaux, probably in
autumn, for the deportation of 1,560 Jews between July 1942 and
May 1944, when he was secretary general of the Prefecture of
Gironde.
</P>
<P>
-- The old "dog of war" of Belgium, Christian Tavernier, is
back in Zaire to help recapture the land lost to the rebels. He
has recruited 280 white soldiers, including Serbs, Croats, Poles,
Russians, Belgians, Italians and French, to join the
counter-offensive by the Zairean government force against the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
-- Algerian President Liamine Zeroual will address the nation
on television this evening, as the violence escalates in his
country during the Muslim fasting month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- After Switzerland, Sweden is being questioned about its past
links with Nazi Germany. An inquiry published this week shows that
the Swedish government, while claiming neutrality during World War
II, knew that the iron it sold to Hitler's Germany was paid with
the gold robbed from Jews. 
</P>
