<HEADLINE> Coup Suspect Complains of Torture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Alleged torture and
forced confessions were conducted at the treason trial of eight
soldiers including a woman Sergeant, now going on in the west
African state of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
At the trial's session today, third accused Joseph Yajah told
Judge Henry Cowan that plainclothes police officers gave him
''electric shocks and burned'' his head with cigarettes to force
him to change his statement.
</P>
<P>
Yajah, led in evidence by defense lawyer Gabriel Baion, said
the officers took him from the maximum security prison (in the
capital) last September where he was detained in connection with
the coup plot to the Criminal Investigation Department (CID)
where the deputy head of the organization, Samuel Soumassa urged
him to change his statement.
</P>
<P>
''I refused,'' Yajah said, ''and I was then tied to a chair in
the crack squad office.''
</P>
<P>
He went on, ''I was stripped naked, ice water was poured on me
and a cable from a tape recorder was plugged into a socket and i
was given four terrible shocks. The officers stuffed a cap in my
mouth when i screamed in agony.''
</P>
<P>
Yajah, a former security officer at state house also claimed
that a sub inspector put out a cigarette ''on his head'' and
"ordered other men to scratch my back with wire. they also
prevented a Sierra Leone Red Cross official from seeing me
afterwards.''
</P>
<P>
Yajah who showed the court wounds he said he received from the
torture, later signed confessions under pressure.
</P>
<P>
A police inspector in the trial later denied Yajah's
accusation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
