<HEADLINE> All Chinese Called to Unite for Reunification (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- A call to all Chinese people,
including Taiwan compatriots, to unite and contribute to the
reunification of the motherland was issued at a meeting which
ended in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting gathered together in the Chinese capital
the directors and deputy directors of Taiwan affairs offices from
across China.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Qian Qichen, member of the Political
Bureau of the Chinese Communist Party Central Committee and
vice-premier of the State Council, said that the present
international and domestic situation is conducive to the curbing
of Taiwan authorities' splitting activities.
</P>
<P>
Despite any change by the Taiwan authorities in its political
system, the internationally recognized fact that Taiwan has been
part of China's territory will never be changed, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Qian asked departments at various levels to continue to carry
out Chinese President Jiang Zemin's important speech on the
promotion of the reunification of the motherland, and take measures
to actively promote the relationship across the Taiwan Straits and
push forward the process of peaceful reunification.
</P>
<P>
The meeting described the year of 1996 as an unordinate one for
the growth of the relations across the straits.
</P>
<P>
It noted that phased important results have been scored in the
struggle against splitting activities and "Taiwan independence",
which fully shows the Chinese people's strong determination and
capability to safeguard national sovereignty and territorial
integrity.
</P>
<P>
The demand for furthering such relationship by the compatriots
across the Taiwan Straits, and the prompt realization of
direct mail, trade links and air and shipping services has become
stronger by the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
