<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Rejects Incorrect Press Reports on Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus today rejected some
incorrect press reports that the tourism on this eastern
Mediterranean island has been hit as a result of the Cyprus
government's decision to buy anti-aircraft missiles from Russia.
</P>
<P>
In an official statement to Xinhua, the Cyprus Tourism
Organization (CTO), a semi-government organization responsible for
 the planning, promotion and marketing of the tourist industry,
said it has no confirmed information of any tourist cancellations
because of the decision of the government to buy defensive
anti-aircraft missiles.
</P>
<P>
The CTO's statement came following the press reports that the
Cyprus' government's decision to buy Russian-made missiles could
hit island's tourism and damage its economy.
</P>
<P>
Kyriakos Jacovides, a CTO official who signed the statement
for the Director General, told Xinhua that the situation in
Cyprus is very normal and peaceful.
</P>
<P>
"As a proof of that, we can invoke the decision of about 250
football teams from Central and North Europe to have their Winter
preparation in Cyprus between February and mid-March," he said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, he added that a Scandinavian Football Cup will
take place in Cyprus from February 20 to March 2.
</P>
<P>
As part of Winter tourism, the Akamas International Chamber
Music Festival will take place in the western coastal town of
Paphos from February 8 to February 23, in which world famous
soloists and ensembles will participate, Jacovides said.
</P>
<P>
The official also told Xinhua that at present, more than 400
travel agents and conference organizers from different countries
of the world are gathering in Cyprus, aimed at promoting the
island as a quality and peaceful tourist destination.
</P>
<P>
Tension has escalated on the island after Cyprus signed on
January 4 a contract with Russia to buy 400 million U.S. dollars
worth of surface-to-air S-300 missiles with a range of 150
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The deal has triggered U.S. criticism and Turkey has
threatened that it will strike at the missiles if they are
deployed.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus Mail reported Tuesday that Cyprus bookings by British
holidaymakers are down this month by as much as 40 percent,
mainly because of the recent "missile crisis."
</P>
<P>
Tour operator said that British holidaymakers make up the bulk
of tourists to Cyprus and January is the month when they make
most bookings, estimated between 10 to 15 percent of the annual
total.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the reservations for the Summer of 1997, Jacovides
said "it is too early to draw any conclusions."
</P>
<P>
"We know that 1997 will be a difficult year, especially due to
the intense international competition in the field of tourism,
but we expect that tourist arrivals will be about the same number
as last year," the official said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, more than 2 million foreign tourists visited the
island, from whom the country earned about 1.6 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In a recent meeting in Nicosia, CTO Chairman Antonis
Andronikou predicted a very difficult year ahead for island's
tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
However, he revealed that in an effort to reverse the
unfavorable situation, the CTO has adopted a new marketing
technique which aims at enhancing Cyprus' image abroad by
emphasizing quality, environment, human factor and the island's
culture.
</P>
<P>
Efforts are also underway to promote specialized packages for
conferences, sports, special interests and agrotourism. Emphasis
is also being placed on tourist packages for senior citizens,
according to Andronikou.
</P>
<P>
Tourism provides 21 percent of the Gross Domestic Product
(GDP) and represents 40 percent of total foreign currency
earnings for this island country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
