<HEADLINE> Germany Urges India to Further Open up Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Germany today wanted India to
open up its insurance sector and give free-market access in the
service field.
</P>
<P>
Visiting German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel, who was
addressing a joint news conference along his Indian counterpart
I.K. Gujral, said India must create a sound infrastructural base
to attract greater investments from abroad.
</P>
<P>
Assuring that Germany would continue to invest in India, Kinkel
said the on-going economic liberalization in India must proceed at
a brisk pace while at the same time ensuring "transparency" in all
government decisions.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel, who arrived here on Thursday for a three-day official
visit, said Germany was willing to assist India in developing its
infrastructure like in the fields of telecommunications, road and
ports.
</P>
<P>
The German foreign minister also said he had "canvassed" for
the airbus industries during his visit here and wanted the Indian
government to choose its version of medium capacity long range
aircraft for Air India.
</P>
<P>
Germany has a major stake along with France in the airbus
consortium. 
</P>
