<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Return Expected to Benefit Inland Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's return to Chinese
sovereignty in July will help inland companies to raise funds on
the world capital market, according to securities officials and
experts.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong will help inland Chinese enterprises in pooling
funds from the world market by remaining as the major venue
for their listings overseas, the officials and experts said during
a conference on overseas listings.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong has become a gathering place for Chinese companies
listed overseas and will remain so in the future," an official of
the Department of International Operations of the China Securities
Regulatory Commission (CSRC), told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The reason is that Hong Kong is closely linked to the mainland
geographically, culturally and historically, he explained, noting
that such connections will grow stronger after its July 1 return.
</P>
<P>
The Securities Commission of the State Council, China's highest
administrative body, announced the fourth group of 38 state-owned
Chinese enterprises for overseas listing in late December.
</P>
<P>
As the date of Hong Kong's return to the mainland is
approaching, the golden time for inland companies to be listed
overseas has arrived, according to Edgar Cheng, chairman of the
Stock Exchange of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"It's the right time to list mainland companies overseas and to
consolidate Hong Kong's position as a `home market' for mainland
firms," Cheng said, adding that his exchange is very optimistic
about the prospects for listing inland enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four of the 26 Chinese companies listed overseas since
1993 landed in Hong Kong, raising a total of 27.2 billion Hong
Kong dollars so far.
</P>
<P>
Observers say that Hong Kong's status as a major financial
center in the world, and its close link with the inland have
enabled Chinese enterprises to effectively raise much-needed funds
from the international capital market.
</P>
<P>
Listing shares in Hong Kong has also helped Chinese firms to
improve their operations, and made their products better known
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Major inland Chinese firms, mostly the most efficient in the
sectors such as the heavy industry, energy and construction, have
in turn helped improve the structure of the Hong Kong securities
market and strengthened Hong Kong's role as a global financial
hub, observers say.
</P>
<P>
"We agree with the CSRC on this point," Cheng said.
</P>
<P>
However, the CSRC official said that listing shares overseas
provides an opportunity for further development, but does not mean
everything.
</P>
<P>
"Enterprises must make good use of the opportunity to improve
their operations and efficiency," he noted.
</P>
<P>
His view was shared by Wang Delin, a delegate to the conference
from the Jilin Chemical Industrial Company, which was listed in
Hong Kong over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that it is less expensive for Chinese companies to
raise funds at home.
</P>
<P>
But the non-standard disclosure of information and irregular
operations have made domestic listing of limited use in helping
enterprises transform their operating mechanisms, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese enterprises will feel compelled to improve their
operations only after they enter a developed capital market like
Hong Kong's," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Power Rationing to Ease by June in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The current power rationing
will ease by the end of June this year under the Least Cost Power
Expansion Program for the next five years, the Kenya Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted out-going Minister of Energy Katan Ngala as
disclosing here on Thursday that the World Bank had released 125
million U.S. Dollars toward Kenya's electricity expansion
program.
</P>
<P>
The money is used to implement projects under the Least Cost
Power Expansion Program, said Ngata who has been transferred to
the Ministry of Lands and Settlement.
</P>
<P>
The current power generation capacity in Kenya stands at 800
megawatts while neighboring Uganda is supposed to supply a
maximum of 30 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, another 88 megawatts will be added to the
existing power generation capacity in the first half of this year
to address the current rationing of power in the east African
country.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the Kenyan government announced the
decentralization of the operations of the Kenya Power and
Lighting Company (KPLC) and the establishment of the Kenya Power
Company to deal exclusively with the generation of electricity in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The KPLC will continue to be responsible for the transmission
and distribution of electricity throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The power expansion program and the operation restructuring
would help ease the power shortage in Kenya, which has become one
of the bottlenecks adversely effecting the growth of all sectors
in Kenya's economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
