<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK Raps Japanese Right-Wing Militarism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Japan should take a resolute
step to reckon with its past war crimes in order to win back the
trust of the international community, said the daily Rodong Sinmun
of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) today.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese authorities cannot escape the historic
responsibility for its past aggression and crimes, said the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The successive post-war governments of Japan have never
admitted the crimes against the Korean people, who had been
subject to a 40-odd-year Japanese colonial rule, it said.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the Japanese governments have sought to whitewash and
justify what the newspaper called "thrice-cursed" war crimes.
</P>
<P>
Rodong Sinmun said Japan has encountered overwhelming
opposition against its attempt to become a permanent member of the
United Nations Security Council as a result of its refusal to
reckon with its past history of aggression.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper cited Germany as a good example, saying it has
won the trust of international community because it officially
admitted its war crimes against mankind and apologized for them.
</P>
<P>
Last year Japan triggered waves of protest from other Asian
countries after Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto visited
the Yasukuni Shrine, which holds tablets of many Japanese war
criminals, and the ruling Liberal Democratic Party decided to
request visiting foreign envoys to pay homage to the shrine.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Takami Eto, a member of the Japanese House
of Representatives, reportedly said that the treaty that
effectively put the Korean Peninsula under Japanese rule was a
"country-to-country treaty" which can hardly be called invasion.
</P>
<P>
He also doubted the credibility of the claim of Korean "comfort
women" who were forced into sexual slavery by the Japanese army
during World War II. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opposition Responsible for All Blasts: Nigerian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The police authority of Nigeria
said the National Democratic Coalition (NADECO), an opposition
organization, is responsible for the bomb blasts that hit the
country in recent times, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
The inspector-general of the police, Alhaji Ibrahim Coomassie,
revealed this at a press briefing at the police force
headquarters in Abuja on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The police head said that investigations by a special task
force have led to conclusive evidences of NADECO's involvement in
those acts of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
He continued that the police is also investigating the
involvement of some foreign countries in the spate of bomb
explosions.
</P>
<P>
The police specifically accused four persons of deep
involvement, which are retired Lieutenant-General Alani
Akinrinade, now self-exiled in London, chief Olu Falae, a former
finance minister; Dr. Amos Arogundade Akingba, a businessman and
Nelson Kassim, a computer expert also based in London.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Amos Akingba was declared wanted for harboring Nelson
Kassim and funding his 12 trips between London and Lagos on
errands connected with explosion conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
Nelson Kassim had died in a car bomb on November 14, 1996 on
his way to the Lagos international airport. It is believed Kassim
was holding a bomb on his lap when the accident happened.
</P>
<P>
The police said Akingba's residence at no. 7, Sule Abuka
Cresent, Ikeja, Lagos, a property of Akingrinade, was the
operational base of all the bomb attacks so far recorded in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Akingba was arrested after the November 14 bomb but later
jumped police bail and fled to London. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
