<HEADLINE> S. Korea Allows 7 Firms to Do Business in DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government today
permitted seven South Korean companies to do business in the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) through contact with
DPRK people in a third country.
</P>
<P>
The seven firms include Korea Green Cross and Taechang, which
have already been allowed to do business in the DPRK, Donghae
Tongsang, National Services, Lotte, LG International and Shin Won.
</P>
<P>
Such permits had not been issued since last September when
South Korea accused 26 armed DPRK military personnel of
"infiltrating into" the country from a grounded submarine.
</P>
<P>
Korea Green Cross, which was allowed in September 1995 to
invest in the DPRK, plans to invest 3 million U.S. dollars in the
construction of a pharmaceutical plant, while Taechang, which
received its go-ahead in last April, will invest 5.8 million
dollars in the development of mineral water springs.
</P>
<P>
Donghae Tongsang plans to invest in a granite quarry in the
DPRK, National Services in duck meat production and processing,
Lotte in food and beverages, LG International in television set
assembly and Shin Won in textiles.
</P>
<P>
On December 29 last year, Pyongyang issued a statement,
expressing "deep regret" over the submarine incident that caused
the "tragic loss of human life." The statement was welcomed by
Seoul. 
</P>
</TEXT>
