<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 09:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Willing to Renew Dialogue with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister
Abdul Karim Kabariti has sent a letter to his Israeli
counterpart Binyamin Netanyahu and Foreign Minister David Levy
this week, calling for a renewal of the dialogue between the
two countries in view of the Hebron accord.
</P>
<P>
According to an Israel Radio report this morning, the
letter was delivered personally to Netanyahu and Levy by Omar
Rifai, Jordan's Ambassador to Israel.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Kabariti praised the Israeli and Palestinian
leaders for reaching the Hebron accord, and hoped that peace would
gain as a result. "The leaders of Israel have shown courage in
shouldering their responsibility in nurturing peace in the Middle
East," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We salute the leadership of Israel and the Palestinian
people for their courage and fortitude in overcoming the
numerous obstacles which delayed signing the agreement," the
letter read.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian prime minister also said that his country
would continue to support all peace builders in the region
to the best of its ability and resources.
</P>
<P>
"Jordan's commitment to build and sustain a strong peace in
the Middle East, built on mutual trust and confidence, and
on warm relations among all the peoples of the region, is
unwavering," he said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
The move ended the strain that has cast a shadow over
the bilateral relations for the last several months since Israel
opened the Western Wall Tunnel exit in Jerusalem's Old City
last September.
</P>
<P>
The first sign of rapprochement was evident earlier this month
when Jordan's King Hussein stopped in Tel Aviv after visiting
Gaza to broker the compromise that helped seal the accord on the
Hebron redeployment and further Israeli pullbacks in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Israeli officials in Jerusalem as saying
that the challenge for Netanyahu and Hussein would be to
renew their personal relationship and thus revive bilateral ties
between the two states.
</P>
<P>
Hussein, who revered Rabin for being a clear-eyed realist
about moderate and radical forces in the region, did not
enjoy the same close relationship with Rabin's successor, Shimon
Peres.
</P>
<P>
The Netanyahu-Hussein personal links suffered a key setback
after Hussein blamed the prime minister for an inconclusive
end to a Washington summit, which occurred in the aftermath
of the tunnel incident.
</P>
<P>
At the time, Hussein blamed Netanyahu for an "arrogance of
power."
</P>
<P>
Rifai said that Jordan could anticipate a visit by Netanyahu to
Jordan, but did not believe it would occur before the end of
Ramadan, the Islamic holy month of fasting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
