<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya, EU Sign Grant Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
signed 23.6 million U.S. Dollars grant agreements with the
European Union (EU) to carry out several projects, according to a
Daily Nation report today.
</P>
<P>
About 5.6 million Dollars out of the amount will be used to
fund a four-year tsetse control project covering Kenya, Uganda,
Tanzania, Rwanda and Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's Micro-Enterprise Support Program will receive more
than 12 million Dollars while the Technical Education Support
Program will get over 6 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The financial accords were signed by EU Head of Delegation to
Kenya Lutz Salzmann and Kenyan Minister for Finance Musalia
Mudavadi.
</P>
<P>
The Micro enterprise support project is aimed at improving
performance of business with up to 10 employees and a potential
to grow.
</P>
<P>
Following the signing of the pacts, Mudavadi said the funding
of micro enterprises will assist Kenya in alleviating poverty
through credit provision, product and skill development support
to small-scale enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that the tsetse fly control project is part
of a regional effort which is expected to improve livestock
productivity.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, the EU head of delegation pointed out
that the technical education support program is intended to
support the policy formulation process.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that a high level delegation from the European
Union will visit Kenya at the end of this month to sign a
financing agreement amounting to about 200 million Dollars for
the next five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
