<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 08:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Syrian Talks Possiblly to Resume in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The stalled Israeli-Syrian
peace talks could resume in this spring, Israeli Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai was quoted as saying today.
</P>
<P>
The minister was quoted by the state-run Israel Radio as
saying that, before the talks are resumed, the two sides should
find ways to reach understandings and scale down the threatening
language.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the continued stalemate in the peace talks and
the tension in south Lebanon could lead to explosion.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said that Israel was doing its utmost to calm down
the situation, but he repeated his objection to Israel's
unilateral withdrawal from the occupied south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Army Chief of Staff Amnon Lipkin Shahak
said he did not think a war with Syria was possible in the near
future. But he did not entirely rule out the possibility of an
armed conflict "at some point," a term that he declined to
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Shahak noted that Syria was truly interested in making peace
with Israel one year ago, but now it has changed its stand.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted Israeli officials as saying that Syria
intended to use terrorism as a leverage in dealing with Israel
in the absence of the progress in peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Following the recent Hebron redeployment, Israel seems to be
shifting its attention to resuming the peace talks with Syria by
repeatedly waving olive branches to Damascus.
</P>
<P>
In a move signaling Israel's flexibility in future talks,
Foreign Minister David Levy said Wednesday that Israel would
accept the United Nations Resolution 242 as basis for resuming
talks with Syria. The resolution calls for returning the
territories that Israel seized in the 1967 War in order to seal
peace.
</P>
<P>
Syria, however, has rejected Israel's latest peace calls,
insisting that the talks should only be restarted from the point
where they broke off last year, namely on the basis of the
understanding which it reached with the Israel's previous Labor
government.
</P>
<P>
In the unsigned understanding, Israel declared its willingness
to totally withdraw from the Golan Heights, which Israel seized
in 1967 from Syria, in return for sealing a peace pact with
Syria.
</P>
<P>
The current Likud government vowed in its police guidelines
never to relinquish the Golan Heights under excuses of
protecting its northern border and valuable water resources.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Syrian peace talks broke off last March after a
series of Islamic suicide bomb attacks in Israel killed 58
people. Since the hardline Likud government came to power last
June, a military stand-off has been brewing in the border,
fueling fears about a possible war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
