<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Debt Relief Yields 93 Million Dollars Saving for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
is likely to save about 93 million U.S. Dollars on its 1996/97
budget, following the cancellation of about 1,000 million Dollars
by the Paris Club last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Acting Finance Minister Daniel Yona told reporters here on
Thursday that the debt relief granted to Tanzania by the club
included the cancellation of the 1,000 million Dollars debt and
rescheduled payment of a 700 million Dollars debt.
</P>
<P>
The minister, however, noted that for the relief to be
meaningful, the government must achieve its 1996/97 fiscal plans
or surpass the revenue collection target.
</P>
<P>
Yona returned from Paris on Wednesday, where he led the
country's delegation for talks with donors of the club.
</P>
<P>
The Paris Club groups Austria, Belgium, Brazil, Canada,
France, Germany, Italy, Japan, The Netherlands, Norway, Britain
and the U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the country's debt to Paris Club member
countries stood at 2,349 million Dollars, out of which 900
million Dollars constituted arrears.
</P>
<P>
He said under terms set by the club only 1,700 million Dollars
were eligible for consideration for relief, out of which 1,000
million Dollars were written off.
</P>
<P>
The club members have also agreed to reschedule repayment of
700 million Dollars for 23 years, including a six-year grace
period, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
