<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Needs Fund to Rebuild Cattle Herd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 24 (Xinhua) -- A survey being carried out by
the Cattle Producers Association of Zimbabwe has revealed that
over 16 million u.s. dollars is required to rebuild the depleted
commercial herd.
</P>
<P>
A market report in the latest Commercial Farmers Union's
"Farmer" magazine said as of January 10, 330 farmers had replied
to the survey, indicating they would require at least 16.5
million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Industry experts however said on Thursday the required funding
was a conservative figure as earlier indications had shown that
up to 30 million U.S. Dollars would be needed to buy cows.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's commercial breeding herd now stands at about
450,000 head, excluding breeding cows owned by small-scale
farmers, compared with 650,000 before the devastation 1991/92
drought.
</P>
<P>
Since then, efforts to rebuild the commercial herd have been
hampered by the shortage of cheap finance, forcing many farmers
to sell breeding cows to repay loans incurred during the drought
years.
</P>
<P>
The government, in a bid to help the farmers, has since
approached donors to provide funds to help rebuild the commercial
herd, which would in turn improve the supply of beef to both the
domestic and export markets.
</P>
<P>
Already, the state-owned Cold Storage Company is failing to
fulfill its annual European Union beef export quota of 9,100 tons
due to the shortage of slaughter stock, largely attributed to the
delay in rebuilding the national herd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
