<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Second to Japan in Foreign Exchange Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- China has become the second
largest holder of hard currency reserves, next only to Japan.
</P>
<P>
Latest figures released by the People's Bank of China, the
central bank, show that the country's foreign exchange reserves
grew a record 31.5 billion US dollars in 1996 to 105 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that a trade surplus and a big inflow of overseas
capital are the two major factors behind the rapid growth.
</P>
<P>
China posted a trade surplus of 12.24 billion US dollars last
year, despite a substantial cut in the overall import tariff level
and in export rebates.
</P>
<P>
Overseas capital inflow into China, which consists mainly of
direct foreign investment and international loans, reached 51
billion US dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Experts say they expect China's hard currency reserves to
grow another 10-20 billion US dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Supported by a rapidly-growing foreign exchange reserve, which
was merely 21.2 billion US dollars at the end of 1993, the Chinese
yuan has consolidated against a basket of hard currencies led by
the US dollar.
</P>
<P>
The yuan edged up nearly 0.3 percent against the greenback in
1996, following a rise of 1.5 percent and 2.9 percent in 1995 and
1994, respectively. It was quoted at 8.2954 against the dollar
today, compared with 8.3174 early last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
