<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Expanding Onshore Oil Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- China has signed 12 onshore oil
contracts with foreign oil companies in the past year, making
great strides in expanding Sino-foreign onshore oil cooperation.
</P>
<P>
According to the China National Petroleum Corporation (CNPC),
China has now signed 30 onshore oil contracts with 35 foreign oil
companies from nine countries and regions, with contracted areas
covering 206,000 square kilometers and total investment amounting
to 770 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation has extended from risk exploration to the
development of oil resources in complex geological structures,
enhancement of oil extraction rates in aging oil fields, as well
as upgrading of oil production technologies.
</P>
<P>
CNPC noted that China will expand onshore oil cooperation this
year by inviting bids for risk exploration, as well as development
of new oil blocks. The corporation's target is the signing of four to
six oil contracts and absorbing 150 million US dollars in foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
CNPC expects the total number of oil contracts to top 20 by end
of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
