<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 07:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ousted Afghan President in Tehran for Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Ousted Afghan President
Burhaneddin Rabbani arrived here Thursday night to attend the
Afghan Peace Conference which is to start Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that Rabbani's
delegation is made up of senior representatives of the Council for
Defense of the Motherland.
</P>
<P>
Ousted Afghan Prime Minister Gulbuddin Hekmatyar is accompanying
Rabbani. Almost all Afghan groups, including the Taleban group,
are expected to participate in the conference, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
The conference, titled "Struggle for Peace in Afghanistan,"
will see the gathering of representatives of all Afghan warring
factions as well as those of Pakistan and the United Nations
organization. The conference is sponsored by Iran.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani was quoted by the report as saying that the only way
to solve the Afghan crisis is to come up with a broad based
government.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Deputy Foreign Minister Alaeddin Boroujerdi said Thursday
night that the response of the Taleban group to the invitation
for the Afghan peace conference in Tehran would test their
claims to peace.
</P>
<P>
Boroujerdi claimed that this is the first time in several
years that senior leaders of all Afghan factions would be
participating.
</P>
<P>
The presence of Rabbani and Hekmatyar at the conference
promises good results for peace in Afghanistan, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said Iran has officially invited the Taleban for the peace
conference, but unfortunately, no response has so far been
received from this group.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan crisis has no military solution, he noted, the
only way out of the present impasse was negotiations between
the different parties and groups in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The fall of Kabul on September 27 is considered as a
major setback in Iran's foreign policy. Iran called the Taleban
as a hand raised group, which has flourished as a result of
U.S. planning, Saudi financial support and Pakistan's logistical
backing.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been supporting the deposed government, which allied
with the faction of northern Uzbek warlord Abdul Rashid Dostam
after losing Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Fighting has continued north of Kabul between the Taleban
and the alliance opposing it, with clashes also reported between
Taleban and its rivals in the northwestern region in the
vicinity of Dostam's base. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
