<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disaster Threatens Victoria Falls: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 24 (Xinhua) -- World Conservation Union (IUCN)
regional director Yemi Katerere warned of a pending ecological
disaster at Victoria Falls if the governments of Zimbabwe and
Zambia do not cooperate to protect it from over-development.
</P>
<P>
Addressing 200 delegates attending the two-day Zimbabwe
Council for Tourism Congress in Bulawayo on Thursday, Katerere
said to date there was no common policy on planning and managing
the town's resources on both sides of the border.
</P>
<P>
This had resulted in conflicting land use and management
practices, conservation and tourism development.
</P>
<P>
The prime resort center, which is one of the seven wonders of
the world, straddles the Zambezi river which forms a common
border between Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
''Victoria Falls is a gold mine to both countries so it is
difficult for them to reach a consensus because stakes are
high,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Despite recommendations made by IUCN to the two countries in a
study last year, Katerere said, the governments had not done much
to implement them.
</P>
<P>
The study which said there were currently too many visitors to
the resort town resulting in over-development, which has a
capacity of accommodating 825,000 visitors annually.
</P>
<P>
Katerere warned that lack of coordination between the two
governments in planning and licensing led to the granting of
licenses which did not bear a relationship to the state of the
environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
