<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Trade Increasing in Shandong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, January 24 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province
recorded 15.35 billion U.S. dollars worth of imports and exports
in the first 11 months of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The figure represented a nearly 17 percent increase from the
same period in 1995, according to the Provincial Commission of
Foreign Trade and Economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Overseas-backed enterprises contributed almost half of the
total exports in the province, where 810 enterprises have been
authorized to manage imports and exports independently.
</P>
<P>
The province has also made efforts to improve its investment
environment and investment promotion methods, as well as to
provide better guidance to exporters.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last November, the province had approved the
establishment of 29,800 overseas-backed businesses, with overseas
investment amounting to 15.73 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
During the January-November period in 1996, the province used
2.47 billion U.S. dollars of overseas funds, a rise of 12
percent from the same period in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The province signed agreements for 780 new projects and labor
cooperation projects in the first 11 months of last year, and
completed 250 million U.S. dollars worth of business, both showing
big increases compared with the same period of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
It also made an investment of 12 million U.S. dollars, and set
up 17 new ventures in overseas areas last year, according to local
officials.
</P>
<P>
Various development zones have continued to expand in the
province. A total of 823 new businesses were initiated in the
zones in the first 11 months of last year, including 355 which
were foreign-backed involving 1.42 billion U.S. dollars in foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
The development zones generated 20.6 billion yuan of industrial
output value, and earned 886 million U.S. dollars from exports in
the first 11 months of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
