<HEADLINE> Japan to Make More Investment in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Bank of
Tokyo-Mitsubishi will sign an agreement next week with Investment
South Africa to help bring more Japanese investment into the
country, local daily "the Star" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The vehicle, natural resources and tourist industries are the
most likely candidates for Japanese business ventures in South
Africa, Kenji Yoshizawa, the bank's deputy president and head of
its foreign division was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Yoshizawa said there was also a possibility of establishing
vehicle-related component industries in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi is believed to be the biggest
bank in the world while Investment South Africa is the
government-funded national investment promotion agency.
</P>
<P>
Japanese firms have already invested more than one billion
Rand (215 million U.S. dollars) in South Africa since 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to Japanese embassy data, there have been 21
joint-venture and technology transfer agreements between Japanese
and South African companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
