<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetans to Face More Employment Opportunities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- With their increased vocational
skills, Tibetans now stand a better chance of getting a job.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, at least 15,000 people in the Tibet Autonomous Region
attended vocational training courses, including classes on
cooking, general office duties, and procedures followed by those
working in state firms.
</P>
<P>
Vocational training centers are widespread in the region,
according to the regional government, which has adopted a series
of special measures, such as tax-free policies in certain fields,
to encourage the opening of such schools.
</P>
<P>
Tibet, traditionally a backward mountainous region, now faces
the challenges of modernization. Power plants and other factories
have been established in the region, which have benefitted the new
generations of the ethnic minority Tibetan groups.
</P>
<P>
Farmers and herdsmen, some of them illiterate, are being urged
by the government to learn about modern industry and technology.
</P>
<P>
Sources with the regional government revealed that in some
regions, vocational schools have vowed to teach any work skill the
students lack.
</P>
<P>
Some officials suggested that, in the long run, every Tibetan
will not only become literate, but also have some knowledge of
technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
