<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India-Latin America Trade Doubles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Trade between India and Latin
American countries rose from 480 million US dollars in 1995 to 960
million in 1996, registering a 100 percent growth, the Hindustan
Times said today.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Indian Minister of State for Commerce B.
B. Ramaiah while inaugurating an international conference on
India-Latin America economic cooperation here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said that India and Trinidad and Tobago will sign a trade
treaty today (January 24) to promote bilateral trade and
investment between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
This manifests the policy of the Indian government to promote
trade with the Latin American countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ramaiah said that lack of shipping, banking, telecom and direct
dialing and transportation facilities are areas which come in the
way of augmenting trade between India and Latin American
countries.
</P>
<P>
He said appropriate arrangements such as organizing exhibitions
and improving shipping services have to be made to facilitate
merchandise movement between India and Latin America.  
</P>
</TEXT>
