<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Asks More Students to Come Back From Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- China's Vice-Premier Li Lanqing
has asked that more Chinese students return to their homeland
after they finish their schooling in foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
When meeting Thursday with representatives attending a national
meeting on the subject, Li said that the Party and the government
have always viewed these students as national treasures, and China
welcomes them to serve their motherland in various ways.
</P>
<P>
He vowed to create a better domestic environment for those
students who have returned.
</P>
<P>
To modernize China, the nation's unremitting efforts are
needed, the official noted, and the contributions of the young
people, including the students who have learned new information
and skills abroad, are particularly necessary.
</P>
<P>
A total of 270,000 Chinese have gone abroad for study since the
country initiated reform and opening-up to the outside world in
the late 1970s. To date, 90,000 of them have returned to the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
