<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies Selling Missiles to Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
denied that it has decided to sell sophisticated air-to-air
missiles to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
However, Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon left open the possibility
that Thailand could one day buy the AIM-120 Advanced Medium Range
Air-to-Air missiles (AMRAAM).
</P>
<P>
"We consider all these things on a case-by-case basis," Bacon
told reporters. "Frequently these discussions continue over a long
period of time."
</P>
<P>
The New York Times today quoted some U.S. officials as saying
that Washington has agreed to sell the missiles to Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper reported that the U.S. and Russia are locked in
"a fierce competition" for arms sales to Southeast Asia, with both
countries offering potential purchasers some of the world's most
sophisticated missiles as incentives.
</P>
<P>
Both countries are trying to "drum up sufficient business to
keep the defense manufacturers profitable and ready to serve the
American military," said the report.
</P>
<P>
"Just a few years ago, the United States would permit the sale
of AMRAAMs only to NATO allies," it adds.
</P>
<P>
Bacon told reporters no one has yet introduced missiles of this
capability into Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
"I think I would just like to stick with our policy, which is
we want to be restrained in our sales so that we don't fuel arms
races. And our policy is not to be the first to introduce new
capabilities into an area," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
