<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hubei Province Adopts New Regulation on Poverty Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Hubei Province in central China
has adopted a new regulation to speed up its poverty alleviation
efforts.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said the province is leading the country in
working out such a regulation in accordance with Chinese law.
</P>
<P>
The regulation clarifies the duties and responsibilities of
governments at various levels in saving local poor people from
poverty, and states that poverty-relief funds and projects will be
managed more strictly.
</P>
<P>
In the mid-1980s, the province launched a widespread
poverty-relief program, and the impoverished population has since
dwindled from 7.18 million to 3.05 million.
</P>
<P>
However, the work to reduce poverty in the next several years
will be difficult, local officials said, as most of the poor now
live in remote mountainous areas or places set to be submerged
under reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
Law experts said the regulation is useful in highlighting the
priorities of local poverty relief, and also for promoting work
efficiency among officials and the public.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the Chinese central government initiated a national
program to help the 80 million poor people shake off poverty by
the end of the century. The program is well underway across the
country.
</P>
<P>
Hubei provincial officials say they are working to meet the
goal one or two years ahead of schedule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
