<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China has 100,000 Internet Subscribers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Some 100,000 Chinese people
have become subscribers of the Internet, a senior official with
the Ministry of Electronics Industry said today.
</P>
<P>
According to a national meeting on the electronics industry,
which ends today, about 20,000 Chinese departments are involved in
information services and more than 1,000 databases have been
established across the country.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese capital of Beijing alone has 30 Internet service
outlets, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
China began offering the Internet service to the general public
in June of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Two public networks -- "Chinanet," launched by the Ministry of
Posts and Telecommunications, and the "Golden Bridge Network" set
up by the Ministry of Electronics Industry -- are operating
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China has built four special networks including
one controlled by the elite Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Internet is the largest computer network in the world and also
the largest information databank.
</P>
<P>
Some 150 countries and regions, including 40,000-50,000 local
networks and 60 million people, had gone on-line with the Internet
as of early 1996.
</P>
<P>
Industrial giant IBM has predicted that 100 million computers,
100 computer networks and 500 million people will subscribe to
Internet in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts said that the hook-up with Internet is one of
the most important steps to push forward the information-oriented
construction of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Internet provides information only in English, so an increasing
number of Chinese departments and network companies have developed
and will start information networks in Chinese, and incorporate
them with Internet through China's six international Internet
outlets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
