<HEADLINE> Bosnian Croats Accuse Muslims of Violating Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 23 (Xinhua) -- President of the Bosnian
Muslim-Croat Federation Kresimir Zubak today accused Bosnian
Muslim leaders of violating the Dayton accord by interpreting it
according to their own political interests.
</P>
<P>
Zubak made the remark in Zagreb, capital of Croatia. It came
after Federation Prime Minister Edhem Bicakcic, a Muslim, accused
a Croat deputy prime minister of suspected involvement in an
illegal economic deal.
</P>
<P>
Under the Dayton accord which ended the Bosnian war in 1995,
Bosnia-Herzegovina is split into two semi-autonomous entities, the
Serb Republic and the Croat-Muslim Federation.
</P>
<P>
Muslims and Croats fought each other for 11 months during the
Bosnian war, and in recent weeks tensions between the two have
heightened by their difference on issues like the distribution of
posts in the Federation government, and the establishment of a
Croat autonomous region.
</P>
<P>
Zubak said Muslim leaders' behavior within the Federation
government was the origin of the increasing disputes between the
two sides.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Zubak, who is also the Croat representative of the
three-member Bosnian presidency, was attacked by the Muslims when
he said Muslim leader Alija Izetbegovic was sticking to the idea
of setting up a Muslim country in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Croats decided to boycott the Federation
assembly (parliament) by withdrawing all their representatives
there.
</P>
<P>
They said they would not accept any assembly resolutions
approved merely by Muslim deputies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
