<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Pushes Ahead Despite Embargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Cubans have struggled to push
the country's economy ahead despite the United States' blockade of
more than three decades, and the serious hindrance to development
caused by the Helms-Burton Act of last year, authorities say.
</P>
<P>
Cuba's gross domestic product (GDP) grew by 7.8 percent in
1996. Apart from the prosperity of tourism, increases in sugar,
nickel, tobacco exports also contributed to the growth,
Ibrahim Ferradaz, minister of foreign investment and economic
collaboration said.
</P>
<P>
The Helms-Burton Act, imposed last March by the United States
to tighten the economic embargo on Cuba, aimed to penalize any
foreign companies which did business with the country.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the act, commercial or credit operations in Cuba
were temporarily interrupted or delayed, and interests on loans to
the country rose as high as 14 to 20 percent compared with the
general 10 percent. Merchandise transport fees also increased.
</P>
<P>
Authorities said the U.S. blockade for more than 30 years has
lost the island about 60 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
To attract foreign capital, the Cuban authorities, last June,
approved a law for creating tax-free zones and industrial
parks. The National Bureau of Tax-Free Zones was established last
October.
</P>
<P>
New enterprises have continued to be created and foreign
entrepreneurial delegations have arrived continuously. About 40
joint enterprises were established in Cuba in 1996, bringing the
total number of joint ventures to 260. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Auto Output up 8.4 Percent in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's auto output rose
despite the economic slowdown last year, with 547,317 vehicles
assembled, up 4.12 percent over 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest statistics by the Federation of Thai
Industries' Automobile Industry Club, the number of passenger cars
assembled in Thailand in 1996 totaled 138,579 units, up 8.95
percent.
</P>
<P>
Trucks assembled last year numbered 404,490 units, up 2.4
percent over 1995 and accounting for 73.9 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Among these trucks assembled, one-ton pickups, which are very
popular in Thailand, numbered 251,188, up 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 2,544 station wagons, 1,095 vans and microbuses
and 609 coaches over ten tons were assembled in the country in
1996.
</P>
<P>
However, Thailand's motorcycle output fell significantly to
1.43 million units last year, down nearly 20 percent from the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
The club said that Thailand exported 14,023 vehicles last year,
up 69 percent from the previous year, earning about 170 million
U.S. dollars, an increase of 101.7 percent compared with the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Auto engines and parts exported by Thailand posted 71 million
U.S. dollars last year, up 39.3 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
