<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalai's Fabrications About Tibet Refuted  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As for their accusations of forced sterilization and abortion
in Tibet, the article says, family planning was first introduced
among Han Chinese people in 1975. The policy did not cover urban
Tibetans until 1982, and Tibetans in agricultural and pastoral
areas have never covered by any family planning program, it says.
</P>
<P>
More "bad news" about Tibet created by the prejudiced Western
media is that "the Chinese are pulling down buildings in the
historic old city (Lhasa)," it says, adding that the Dalai Lama
concluded that there is "cultural genocide" in tibet, and that the
tibetans are "living in hell."
</P>
<P>
Records suggest that of the one million people in tibet in 1950
over 900,000 were homeless, and more than 1,000 Lhasa families
relied on begging. The city had a population of only 20,000 at
that time.
</P>
<P>
Today, the article says, rural tibetans have an average of
20.36 square meters of living space, and urban Tibetans 12.59
square meters.
</P>
<P>
It seems that, to Dalai Lama, heaven means tibetans living in
the wilderness and working as poor serfs, the article says.
</P>
<P>
It is true that with rapid economic development tibetans are
refurbishing Lhasa with new buildings, just like Chinese people
are doing in other cities, it says.
</P>
<P>
But the Chinese government and local authorities protect the
cultural and historical relics on the "roof of the world," it
stresses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalai's Fabrications about Tibet Refuted  (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By making accusations against China, the ill-minded Dalai and
his followers, including some Western media, are trying to confuse
people with a picture of an old city with cultural relics being
damaged, the article reports.
</P>
<P>
The fact is that Tibet has been paying great attention to the
protection of its local culture and its historical or religious
buildings, it says.
</P>
<P>
The central government has allocated 216 million yuan to repair
the Potala Palace, the Johkang Monastery and many other religious
buildings in recent years, winning wide acclaim from cultural and
religious leaders in tibet, it reports.
</P>
<P>
In providing material to back up the Dalai Lama's attack on
China "pulling down buildings in old cities," his brother Tendzin
Choegyal affirmed that "new commercial buildings and apartment
blocks have gone up" and that tibet is undergoing "remarkable
changes." At least he admits that Tibet is developing at an
impressive pace, the article says.
</P>
<P>
To encourage the development of tibet, the central government
has never taken any tax or revenue from Tibet but has invested 35
billion yuan in the region since 1952. "Ignoring this, Tendzin
Choegyal, in his recent visit to Germany, warned overseas
investors to ensure that funds for reconstruction projects 'do not
fall into Chinese hands'," the article says.
</P>
<P>
Wearing the cloak of religion, the Dalai Lama has served his
Western and Eastern hosts and sponsors by ferociously attacking
the chinese government and spreading rumors about the situation in
tibet the article points out.
</P>
<P>
It concludes that some people live on their hard work while the
Dalai Lama lives on fabricating rumors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
