<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fininvest Denies Mafia Link </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 23 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for the media-retail
group, Fininvest, denied today that the group had ever paid
rackets fees to the Sicilian mafia or received such requests from
the Cosa Nostra.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after Salvatore Cancemi, an ex-mafioso
turned state witness, told a Palermo court that Fininvest
executive Marcello Dell'Utri had paid an annual "fee" of 200
million lire (about 125,000 U.S. dollars) as protection money for
the group's Sicilian TV transmitter, and for downtown Palermo
properties.
</P>
<P>
"Neither Dell'Utri or other executives of the group ever
responded to extortionary requests, nor did they ever receive
demands for protection money," the Fininvest statement said. It
added that the group had no real estate interests in downtown
Palermo.
</P>
<P>
Cancemi testified today in the trial of Vittorio Mangano, a
stable hand who once worked on the estate of Silvio Berlusconi and
who is accused of organized crime ties. Dell'Utri is also on trial
in Palermo for mafia association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
