<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian President Visits Poland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian president Leonid
Kuchma paid a one-day official visit to Poland Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma and his Polish counterpart Aleksander Kwasniewski met
and discussed issues on bilateral ties, European integration, the
eastward expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) and regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference after the meeting, Kwasniewski said
that Poland supports Ukraine's efforts for European integration.
</P>
<P>
Poland and Ukraine could play an important role in constructive
cooperation and preventing the possible outbreak of tension in the
central European region, the Polish president noted.
</P>
<P>
He held out hope that when he visits Ukraine this May, the two
countries could sign a joint communique on reconciliation so as to
put an end to the past and pursue a better future.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents also said, for the sake of regional
stability, they would accept a proposal put forward by Belarussian
president Exlexander Lukashenko for holding a tripartite summit
meeting among Ukraine, Poland and Belarus.
</P>
<P>
During Kuchma's visit, Poland and Ukraine signed a memorandum
on measures to be taken that will lead eventually to the removal
of trade barriers between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade reached a record high of 1 billion dollars in
1995. The trade volume in the first nine months last year
increased sharply to 1.4 billion dollars, up 39 percent over the
same period of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Poland has now become Ukraine's largest trade partner among the
central European nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
