<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Imposes Counter-Crisis Rule on Bourse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Stock Exchange of Thailand
(SET) has introduced a new regulation that allows the bourse to
suspend trading during crises, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rule that has taken effect, if the SET index
loses 200 points over a given day, trading on the bourse will be
suspended for the balance of the day.
</P>
<P>
When the index drops by 150 points, trading will be suspended
for 90 minutes, while a 100-point fall will cause a 60-minute
suspension.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thailand's Securities and Exchange Commission has
agreed to broaden floating ranges for stock prices, stipulating
that the ceiling price for a stock could rise by 33 percent of its
price and the floor price could drop by 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
Any stocks, which rise to 10 percent of their ceiling prices or
drop to 10 percent of their floor prices in a day, will be allowed
a suspension for 15 to 30 minutes for each rise or fall.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
