<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Primary Exports Fetch Peak Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's primary export
commodities of tea, rubber, coconut and spices reached peak prices
in 1996, according to official sources today.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan tea was sold at 2.3 U.S. dollars per kilogram in
1996 compared with one US dollar in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The price of desiccated coconut shot up from 800 U.S. dollars
per ton in 1995 to 1,400 U.S. dollars in 1996, as did the price of
rubber.
</P>
<P>
Prices of spices increased five folds in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The sources attributed the peak prices to the country's new
strategies in selling its commodities in the world market.
</P>
