<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Currency Hits Six-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Thai baht hit the lowest
level in almost six years Thursday in a continuous sharp decline
against the U.S. dollar in the past weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Thailand, which fixed the mid-rate at 25.79
baht to the dollar, has not intervened, saying that the
depreciation has been strictly a consequence of its use of the
basket of currencies in determining the baht's exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
Each day the bank announces a target rate against the dollar,
with trading allowed around a two-satang (100 satang to the baht)
band in either direction.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand does not reveal the weightings used in the
basket, but analysts believe that the U.S. dollar holds 80
percent, the Japanese yen 12 percent and the German mark 8
percent.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Governor of the Bank of Thailand Chaiyawat Wibulswasdi
denied that a baht devaluation was imminent, saying that the baht
was moving naturally in line with the appreciation of the U.S.
dollar against the yen and mark.
</P>
<P>
The weakening of the baht gives Thai exporters a relative
advantage in the U.S. market, but it is offset by a drop in
competitiveness in their exports to Japan and Germany.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka To Train Teacher Recruits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 24 (Xinhua) -- All new recruits to the
teacher's service in Sri Lanka will be given a pre-service
education before being posted to schools, Higher Education
Ministry sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that this step has been taken to upgrade the
quality of the teaching profession in the country.
</P>
<P>
This project which is jointly funded by the World Bank and the
Asian Development Bank will cost 76 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Under this project, a National Authority on Teacher Education
will be established to coordinate and monitor the proposed
national system of teacher education.
</P>
<P>
The existing Teacher Training Colleges and some colleges of
education will be restructured to form 100 teacher centers
covering all districts in the country.
</P>
<P>
This program is planned to assure all the teachers will be
involved in preservice training and also continuing education in
every five years, the sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
