<HEADLINE> HK Businessmen's Confidence Enhanced: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Businessmen in Hong Kong are
more optimistic about the current quarter than they were about any
quarter in 1996, according to Dunn and Bradstreet's business
expectations survey for the first quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The survey, which was taken late last year, show that all types
of business, except retailers, had increased expectations of
improved sales for this quarter.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers of durable goods were the most optimistic, with
an index number of 71 compared with 47 for the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
The index number is the percentage of respondents expecting an
increase, minus the number expecting a decrease.
</P>
<P>
A net 54 percent of all businesses were expecting increases in
sales and all sectors were higher than the previous quarter, the
survey said.
</P>
<P>
It said that even gloomy shopkeepers had improved feelings
about their net profits.  
</P>
</TEXT>
