<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Plans to Export Oil by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Brazil is planning to become
self-sufficient in hydrocarbons in 1998, and to begin exporting
oil by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Petrobras, a state enterprise and one of the 15 biggest oil
companies in the world, has decided to invest 10 billion
U.S. dollars between 1996 and 2000 to increase production.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's present oil output can only meet 58 percent of its
domestic demand, and domestic consumption is increasing by 6 to 7
percent a year.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's oil output has grown by 20 percent during the past two
years and in 1996 it amounted to a daily average of 809,000
barrels.
</P>
<P>
Petrobras, which has the capacity to pump crude from a depth of
more than 1,000 meters in the sea, recently discovered an undersea
oil field with proven reserves of 1.3 billion barrels. This brings
the proven oil reserves of Brazil to 12.3 billion barrels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
