<HEADLINE> U.N.-Sponsored Forum on Aid for Afghanistan Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 23 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations-sponsored
international meeting on Afghanistan ended today without a unified
program to offer humanitarian assistance to that war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency said more than 300 representatives
from more than 20 countries attended the three-day forum in
Ashgabat, capital of Turkmenistan, and exchanged their views on
the Afghan issue.
</P>
<P>
U.N. special adviser Yasushi Akashi told reporters after the
meeting that he believed that the international community will
eventually draw up a unified program for the humanitarian
assistance to Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
After 17 years of conflicts, Afghanistan is one of the poorest
countries in the world today.
</P>
<P>
The recent escalation of civil war has made even worse the
living conditions of an already impoverished population.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan conflict saw a sudden upsurge as the Taliban militia
launched a lightning offensive last week on the Anti-Taliban
Alliance on the front north of the capital of Kabul. 
</P>
