<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Major Opposition Party Suffers Another </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' biggest opposition
party, the Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino (Laban), suffered
another revolt as 100 members resigned, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The reports said Senator Gloria Macapagal Thursday announced to
bolt the party with about 100 party leaders, who were disgruntled
over how Senator Edgardo Angara has been running the party.
</P>
<P>
"I can not, in conscience, remain in the party that stifles
dissent and demands the unthinking obedience of a robot,"
Macapagal was quoted as saying in a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Macapagal, a presidential aspirant, also led the renegades the
same day to form a new party, the kabalikat ng Malayang Pilipino,
which is expected to participate in the 1998 presidential polls.
</P>
<P>
She said she decided to quit the party because the Angara bloc
in the Senate refused to bring her into the new majority that saw
another Laban stalwart, Senator Neptali Gonzales, being ousted
last October as Senate President.
</P>
<P>
Angara masterminded the coup against Gonzales and installed
Senator Ernesto Maceda, president of the Nationalist People's
Coalition, as the new Senate President.
</P>
<P>
"Why couldn't the plotter have chosen another Laban stalwart to
be Senate President? Now I ask you: who is the real renegade in
Laban?" Macapagal said.
</P>
<P>
Angara's coup resulted in an immediate split in the Laban,
sending dozens of senior officials and some 10,000 members to
leave the party. Most of these members defected to the ruling
Lakas-NUCD coalition.
</P>
<P>
Although Angara expressed regret over Macapagal's decision to
quit the party, he accepted it as her right to do so.
</P>
<P>
He added that he was confident that the mass resignation would
not diminish the Laban's standing as the major opposition party in
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
