<HEADLINE> Venezuelan President To Visit Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan President Rafael
Caldera will make an official visit to Mexico on February 6 and 7.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Caldera is expected to sign an agreement to
prevent double taxation and to revise an extradition treaty,
Venezuelan Ambassador to Mexico, Fernando Ochoa Antich, told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Caldera will also decorate Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo
with the "Order of the Liberator" necklace, and present a statue
of Antonio Jose de Sucre, forefather of Venezuela. This will be
located in Paseo de la Reforma Avenue in the capital, Mexico
City. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Kill 600 Monkeys with Ebola Virus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine environmental
authority has ordered the immediate killing of some 600 monkeys at
a breeding facility in Laguna province, the central Philippines,
to prevent an outbreak of the deadly Ebola virus.
</P>
<P>
Today's Manila Times quoted Environment and Natural Resources
Secretary Victor Ramos as saying that the order was issued after a
six-week investigation by a multisectoral committee showed that
the Ebola Reston Strain continued to infect the monkeys at the
Ferlite farm.
</P>
<P>
"Although there is a remote possibility that it will infect
humans, we will not take the risk," Ramos said, adding that around
600 Philippine macaque monkeys are still at the farm.
</P>
<P>
Ramos also ordered the closure of the Ferlite farm and the
cancellation of its environmental compliance certificate, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The farm was the primate breeding place that exported to the
United States last March two monkeys found to be infected with the
Ebola Reston Strain.
</P>
<P>
The strain took its name from an incident in Reston, Virginia,
the U.S. in 1989 where several Philippine macaque monkeys were
struck by a type of Ebola virus.
</P>
<P>
Ebola, a deadly virus first found in Africa, killed 235 people
in Zaire in 1995 and 13 in Gabon last year.
</P>
<P>
The management of the farm had earlier been given six weeks to
improve its infection control measures to check the spread of the
virus, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
According to findings of the investigation group, the farm
failed to make the required improvement, with an insufficient
supply of "barrier protection materials" such as disinfectants,
masks, gloves and footbaths as well as isolation of animals in the
farm.
</P>
<P>
This prompted the Department of Environment and Natural
Resources to order the killing of all the remaining monkeys by
euthanasia and the incineration of the monkey's carcasses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ChinaSat Buys New Satellite From US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- China will buy another US
telecommunications satellite to replace ChinaSat-7, a commercial
telecommunications satellite that failed to enter its preset orbit
last August, said today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
ChinaSat-8, which will be made and launched into orbit by the
US firm, Space Systems/Loral, will incorporate more advanced
functions than ChinaSat-7, noted Cui Xinzheng, a senior official
with the China Telecommunications Broadcast Satellite Corp
(ChinaSat).
</P>
<P>
The deal is one of China's important measures to promote
telecommunications in the next century, Cui said.
</P>
<P>
ChinaSat-8 will be designed to meet not only the demand of the
country's developing public satellite telecommunications in the
near future, but also the needs of other civilian satellite
communications, the newspaper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
