<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ban Bank Loans To Polluters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Agricultural Bank will no
longer grant loans to small enterprises with serious pollution
problems, according to a joint notice issued by the State Bureau
of Environmental Protection and the bank.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the decision is to stiffen pollution control in
township and village enterprises and to guarantee the safety of
loans made to them, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Last September, the State Council ordered a shutdown of small
factories engaged in 15 different pollution-prone industries,
including pulp-making and hide-processing and dye production.
</P>
<P>
The factories include paper mills with an annual production of
less than 5,000 tons, tanneries producing less than 30,000 pieces
of cow leather annually and factories producing less than 500 tons
of dye a year.
</P>
<P>
Officials of local branches of the agricultural bank who grant
loans to the banned factories will be punished, the notice warned.
</P>
<P>
The branches are also required to recover loans given to the
closed-down factories, whose accounts are to be frozen and their
properties sealed for safe-keeping, the notice said.
</P>
<P>
Local branches are also ordered to make reports before February
20 on the checking and recalling of loans which had been granted
to the factories, said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the notice asked the branches to co-operate with
departments in charge of environmental protection to increase
surveys and checks on borrowers' abilities to prevent and control
pollution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian Police Seize Big Hashish Haul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Romanian police have seized
more than one ton of hashish, worth 15 million U.S. dollars, in
their first major haul of 1997.
</P>
<P>
National television reported today that the hashish was found
in a container of black tea on a ship from South Africa to the
Black Sea port of Constanta, about 200 kilometers east of
Bucharest. The tea was consigned to a company in Bucharest.
</P>
<P>
The police and drug agents are investigating.
</P>
<P>
According to an AP report, the drugs were being smuggled to
Romania from Indochina, but the country from which they originated
was not identified.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian media earlier reported that Romania was becoming a
key staging post for European drug-traffickers. Drugs from the
Middle East, Asia and Latin-America were increasingly being
smuggled to other European countries via Romania.
</P>
<P>
Romanian police had set up an anti-drug directorate and
strengthened cooperation with other European countries to combat
the 'drug invasion'. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
