<HEADLINE> Business News in Brief in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The following is business news
in brief in the Philippines:
</P>
<P>
-- Scandinavian Motors Corp. (SMC) and Viking Cars Inc. (VCI),
exclusive distributors of Volvo cars in the Philippines, are
projecting 1.5 billion pesos (57.3 million U.S. dollars) in total
sales this year or a total of 750 units, including three new
models up for commercial introduction by the middle of 1997. SMC
Vice President for Legal and Administration Alberto Arcillas said
Thursday that the forecast was based on increased demand for more
luxury cars from the more affluent sectors of the middle-age
bracket. The three new models are the S-40, V-40 and Coupe.
</P>
<P>
-- The Philippine National Bank (PNB) expects its net income to
increase by 30 percent this year to about 2.2 billion pesos (about
84 million U.S. dollars), PNB President Peter Favila said Thursday
in a joint briefing with stock analysts and media. The PNB posted
an unaudited net income of 1.71 billion pesos (65.3 million U.S.
dollars) in 1996, marginally higher than its target of 1.7 billion
pesos (64.9 million U.S. dollars). PNB Senior Executive Vice
President Valentin Araneta said the bank's total resources shot up
by 16 percent to 194.4 billion pesos (7.4 billion U.S. dollars) in
1996 from 167 billion pesos (6.4 billion U.S. dollars) in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
