<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Renovate Foreign Trade Administration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- China will seek to renovate the
import and export administration in a bid to create an equally
competitive business environment, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing based English newspaper also said that export
administrative measures will continue to show support for export
products with high added-value, high technology content and famous
brand.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Li Dongsheng, director-general of the foreign
trade administration department of the Ministry of Foreign Trade
and Economic Co-operation, as saying that China will modify the
number of products under import and export quota license to meet
the pace of China's foreign trade development.
</P>
<P>
Li said, there are 143 products under the export quota
administration. The number has decreased sharply from that in the
early 1990s, when more than 200 export items were subject to quota
control.
</P>
<P>
The ministry intends to amend and improve rules guiding the
export quota administration.
</P>
<P>
China will continue to require public bidding on some export
quotas, and in 1997 the practice will involve 33 items, compared
to 30 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The practice is aimed at meeting quotas based on equal
competition and to reduce the practice of some Chinese companies
of cutting export prices to win international market shares.
</P>
<P>
Li added that chambers of commerce are encouraged to play a role
in market co-ordination.
</P>
<P>
Li's department will make an effort to promote the method of
tracing quota licenses, distribution and uses via electronic data
transmission and reinforce the administration over trademarks to
indicate places of original production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Robberies, Hold-ups Decline in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Armed robberies and hold-ups
perpetrated against banks declined by more than half in 1996 in
the Philippines, due to increased vigilance and heightened
security measures jointly taken by banks and the police, the local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
From 20 robberies and hold-ups in 1995, these violent incidents
dropped to nine last year, the reports quoted Governor of the
Philippine Central Bank Gabriel Singson as saying on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Citing a report from the Bankers Association of the Philippines
and the Philippine National Police, Singson said cash losses
dropped to more than 150,000 U.S. dollars last year, from nearly
970,000 dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Singson said the installation of time delay locks in every bank
branch, as mandated by the central bank, greatly helped in the
prevention of armed robberies.
</P>
<P>
Increased police visibility and communication links with police
stations also helped deter hold-ups, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
