<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Post Graduate Exam Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- China's national entrance
examinations for post graduate schools began today, attracting a
record 242,000 examinees.
</P>
<P>
It is the highest number of test takers since the country
resumed granting postgraduate degrees in late 1978, according to
the State Education Commission.
</P>
<P>
The number of applicants this year increased by 38,000, up 18
percent over that of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Among the applicants, 59 percent are unit or enterprise
employees, up 20 percent over last year. Teachers in universities
and middle schools account for 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
The rest are undergraduates, up 15 percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Some 421 universities and 322 other higher learning
institutions will enroll 51,000 students this year, according to
the commission.
</P>
<P>
China has faced a shortage of post-graduate degree holders in
recent years, a result of the rapid development of economy and
society.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
