<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile Has Unfavorable Balance of Trade in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Chile had a 1.227 billion
U.S. dollar trade deficit in 1996 while in the previous year it
had a 1.385 billion dollar trade surplus, the central bank said
today.
</P>
<P>
The total volume of sales abroad in 1996 shrank by 5 percent,
reaching only 15.296 billion dollars, and that of imports grew by
12.7 percent, amounting to 16.523 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The drastic drop in the international market in the price of
copper and cellulose, the two most important export products of
Chile, contributed to a great degree to the trade deficit, the
bank said.
</P>
<P>
Copper price went down from 133.198 dollar cents a pound in
1995, to 103.894 cents in 1996, a 21.88 percent decline, and
cellulose price dropped from 800 dollars a ton to 500 dollars, a
37.5 percent drop.
</P>
<P>
In imports, the amount of intermediate goods increased by 32
percent, consumer goods 18 percent, and capital goods 14 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
