<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian League Again Fails to Elect President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The Italian Soccer League once
again failed to elect a new president after three unsuccessful
ballots on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
None of the candidates received the two-thirds majority (of 38
votes) necessary to win the presidency. Former Italian Soccer
Federation (FIGC) president Antonio Matarress led the candidates
with as many as 17 votes in three straight ballots, with AC
Bologna president Giuseppe Gazzoni Frascara a close second, and
Mediaset managing director Adriano Galliani third.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of 37 Serie A and Serie B clubs failed to elect
a replacement for former president Luciano Nizzola on January 10.
Clubs deadlocked between Matarrese and Frasoara. Nizzola was
named FIGC president in December.
</P>
<P>
Galliani was named as provisional president at the January
assembly.
</P>
<P>
Following the third unsuccessful ballot, organizers decided to
adjourn the assembly unitl a third meeting at an as yet
undetermined date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
