<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Board Meeting Ends Without Accord on Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The executive board of the World
Health Organization (WHO) closed its 99th session here Wednesday
with no agreement on WHO's program budget for the 1998-1999
biennium.
</P>
<P>
"After an extensive debate, members of the board differed on
whether to recommend a 2 percent increase or maintain the level of
budget," said WHO in a press release today. The issue will go to
the 1997 World Health Assembly scheduled to meet in Geneva from
May 5 to 14.
</P>
<P>
The WHO board singled out five priority areas for the program
budget: promotion of primary health care and other related areas;
eradication of specific communicable diseases; prevention and
control of other communicable diseases; and reproductive health,
women's health and family health.
</P>
<P>
The 10-day meeting also discussed the issue of WHO reforms to
improve WHO's effectiveness and efficiency in responding to the
changing needs of member states.
</P>
<P>
The board members examined the renewal of the health-for-all
strategy. Five principles were emphasized during the discussion:
human-centered sustainable development, health policies based on
sound evidence, the "gender perspective," the primary health care
approach and partnerships.
</P>
<P>
One of the resolutions adopted at the meeting requested WHO
Director-General Hiroshi Nakajima "to coordinate the observance of
World Tuberculosis Day on March 24 of each year as an opportunity
throughout the world for organizations concerned to raise public
awareness of tuberculosis as a major urgent public health problem
and for countries to assess progress in tuberculosis control."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Tumble on Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 23 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks plunged this
afternoon in heavy trading, as a jump in interest rates triggered
profit-taking, pulling the Dow Jones industrial average down from
its first piercing through 6,900.
</P>
<P>
The Dow, up more than 56 points shortly after 2 p.m., slid to a
loss of nearly 108 points before steadying and finishing with a
drop of 94.28, or about 1.4 percent, to 6,755.75. Despite the
drop, the Dow has still advanced about 4.8 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-4 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with its volume jumping to 683.80
million shares, an all-time high.
</P>
<P>
Broader measures also fell sharply after spending most of the
session at record levels.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 8.67, or 1.1 percent,
to close at 777.56, erasing an 8.44-point afternoon gain.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 9.71 to 1,378.35 after
surpassing the 1,400 mark for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index fell 3.65 to 409.15, and the American
Stock Exchange composite index fell 1.18 to 589.69.
</P>
<P>
The Dow had rallied in earlier trading as a series of
impressive earnings reports. But the momentum died as bonds turned
lower, boosting the interest rates, as the market absorbed a new
supply of securities from a government auction of 12.5 billion
U.S. dollars in new 5-year Treasury notes.
</P>
<P>
Analysts noted that the financial markets' recent jitters have
been aggravated by fears that the stream of robust profit reports
has enhanced suspicions that the economy may be accelerating at an
inflationary pace.
</P>
<P>
As bonds fell, the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond rose to
6.85 percent from late Wednesday's 6.83 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
