<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon: US Considers START III After Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the United States
and Russia have been seeking further arms reduction between the
two giant military powers, but the U.S. side holds that Russia
should ratify the START II treaty first, a senior U.S. Defense
Department official said today.
</P>
<P>
Defense Department spokesman Keneth Bacon told a news briefing
that U.S. President Bill Clinton and Russian President Boris
Yeltsin and other leaders of the two countries have discussed for
several times the possibility of further reduction of nuclear arms
after the two nations signed the Second Strategic Arms Reduction
Treaty (START II) in 1993.
</P>
<P>
He said that the United States was willing to begin
negotiations on a START III agreement after START II was ratified.
</P>
<P>
"Since... President Clinton and President Yeltsin have talked
about the possibility of moving toward a START III agreement after
START II is ratified, the Pentagon has been looking at what
further force reductions would be possible, would be acceptable,"
Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that the U.S. position has not changed, that
is, the Russian Duma (parliament) must ratify START II first.
</P>
<P>
However, the Russian Duma has yet voted on the treaty because
many Russian legislators were upset by NATO's plan to expand
eastward to include some of the former Warsaw Pact member nations.
</P>
<P>
Moscow has also been balking at the accord on grounds that it
will cost too much to implement and will impel the Russian
government to build additional strategic weapons to maintain rough
parity with the United States at the ceiling the treaty sets.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post reported today that the Pentagon is
secretly studying the impact of an additional cut of 1, 000 to
1,500 nuclear warheads to leave residual forces of as few as 2,000
weapons.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials see that a proposal for new cuts as a way to
persuade Russian legislators to ratify the so-called START II
treaty, which calls for 50 percent cuts in nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
But Bacon said, "we've made it very clear to the Russians on a
number of occasions and at a number of levels that START II is the
step that has to be got to START III negotiations." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
