<HEADLINE> US to Seek UN Action Against Libya Over Landing Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration
said today that it would seek action against Libya at the United
Nations for its airliner landing in Accra, capital of Ghana.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said at a briefing,
"We believe an effort may be under way to test the U.S.
resolutions. We will pursue the matter at the United Nations."
</P>
<P>
He was referring to a Tripoli airliner which was permitted by
Ghana to land in Accra earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
The United States has said that Libya was behind the 1988
bombing of Pan Am 103 over Scotland and has made the United
Nations place sanctions against Libya, including a measure that
forbids international landing rights to Libya's national airline.
</P>
<P>
Ghanian officials reportedly said that they granted the landing
rights to the Tripoli airliner after the pilot said he was out
of fuel and would crash in 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
But the United States would not believe the remarks. 
</P>
