<HEADLINE> US Dollar Inches Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar hit a 47-month
high of nearly 120 yen and touched another 2-year high against the
mark today before retreating to end mixed in New York.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was once traded as high as 119.69 yen, the strongest
since February 1993, before settling at 119.47 yen, up from 119.03
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A late sell-off in the U.S. stock market also helped check the
rise of the dollar. The Dow Jones industrial average, which
surpassed 6,900 in the afternoon for the first time, tumbled
nearly 100 points in the final hour of trading.
</P>
<P>
The strong dollar indicated the currency remained in heavy
demand. Traders predicted it would test the 120-yen level and
probably keep rising against the Deutsche mark.
</P>
<P>
The dollar dropped to 1.6366 mark in New York today, down from
1.6427 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The British pound, which tumbled Wednesday to the lowest level
since October, weakened further in a broad retreat sparked partly
by fears that the governing Conservative Party may have to call
parliamentary elections in March instead of May.
</P>
<P>
In New York the pound cost 1.6292 U.S. dollars, down from
1.6300 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
