<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Nazi Collaborator to Face Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Maurice Papon, former Gaullist
minister and secretary general of the prefecture of Gironde from
1942 to 1944, has become the second Frenchman to face trial over
charge of complicity in crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
After the French supreme court rejected today an appeal by the
86-year-old former Nazi collaborator, Papon lost the last chance
to escape justice for deporting some 2,000 Jews to Nazi death
camps during World War II.
</P>
<P>
He will be summoned by the Investigation Court of Gironde over
charges of complicity in crimes against humanity, and become the
second man after another Nazi collaborator, Paul Touvier, to be
tried over such crimes.
</P>
<P>
The Criminal Chamber of the Cour de Cassation (supreme court),
presided by Judge Christian le Gunehec, rejected five arguments by
the attorney of defense of Papon, who appealed against a decision
by the Bordeaux Appeals Court made in September 1996 to put him on
trial.
</P>
<P>
Attorney Varaut, the defending lawyer of Papon, argued that the
procedure of the case has lasted too long (15 years) and that
Papon was impossible to be an accomplice of the Nazis because he
did not believe in Nazi ideology and because he did not belong to
a criminal group.
</P>
<P>
The court said that the Nuremberg Court which put on trial Nazi
criminals in the wake of World War II did not say that a Nazi
accomplice must believe in Nazi ideology or must join the Nazi
party.
</P>
<P>
Papon himself made an outcry after the court made the decision,
saying that he was being persecuted like Captain Dreyfus, a Jewish
officer of the French army who was wrongly jailed in the late 19th
century for allegedly spying for the Germans.
</P>
<P>
The court decision was welcomed by all civil groups, including
the National Federation of Deportees and Jailed Resistant Fighters
and Patriots, and the Union of Jewish Students of France.
</P>
<P>
The decision also brought to an end a 15-year-old dispute over
the case, which was triggered by the publication in 1981 of some
documents of the Vichy collaboration regime, which was signed by
Papon for the rounding up and deportation of thousands of Jews to
Germany.
</P>
<P>
After France was liberated from Nazi occupation in 1944, Papon
served several prefect's seats and as Paris police commissioner
under the government of President Charles de Gaulle, and was
minister of budget under the government of Prime Minister Raymond
Barre in the 1970s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
