<HEADLINE> US Complains of Saudi Over Bombing Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
complained against Saudi Arabia for withholding information about
its investigation of a truck bombing there that killed 19 American
servicemen last year.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Janet Reno told a news conference today that
Saudi Arabia has failed to turn over "some very important
information" about the June bombing at a U.S. military housing
complex in Dhahran, Saudi Arabia, which she said was needed "to
assess what action should be taken."
</P>
<P>
"I am hopeful that we will be able to address these issues
(and) obtain the information so appropriate steps can be taken,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
Her remarks followed a similar criticism from FBI chief Louis
Freeh, who spoke at a Wednesday lunch with the Washington Post's
editors and reporters.
</P>
<P>
"We have not gotten everything which we have asked for, and
sure, that has affected our ability to make findings or
conclusions, or to channel the investigation in different
directions," today's Washington Post quoted Freeh as saying.
</P>
<P>
At a State Department briefing, spokesman Nicholas Burns said
of Reno and Freeh, "They both spoke for the U.S. government."
</P>
<P>
At the Pentagon, spokesman Kenneth Bacon said U.S. views "have
been expressed very clearly by the director of the FBI."
</P>
<P>
The Saudi embassy had no immediate response to the U.S.
criticism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
