<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Budget Deficit Up in 1st 3 Months of Fiscal 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The budget deficit of the
U.S. government increased by 5.4 percent in the first three months
of fiscal 1997 despite a budget surplus in December, the U.S.
Treasury Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the December surplus totaled 19.4
billion dollars, nearly four times the 5.3 billion surplus a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
Boosted by quarterly tax payments, U.S. government revenues
totaled 148.5 billion dollars in the month, compared with 99.7
billion in October and 97.8 billion in November.
</P>
<P>
Spending in December totaled 129.1 billion, down from 140
billion in October and 135.7 billion in November.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. government was 58.8 billion dollars in the
red during the October-December period, 5.4 percent more than the
deficit during the same three months of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has projected that the deficit in
the current year, starting from October 1 of 1996, would rise to
125.7 billion dollars from 107.3 billion last year because of
spending increases on entitlements such as Social Security and
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government budget deficit hit a record 290.4 billion
dollars in fiscal 1992, and then dropped in each of the following
years. The deficit in fiscal 1996 was the smallest since 79.0
billion in fiscal 1981.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government debt currently stands at 5.2 trillion
dollars resulted from each year's budget deficit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
