<HEADLINE> US Exempts Sudan in Doing Business with US Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration
has exempted Sudan from the 1996 Antiterrorism Act that restricts
U.S. companies from financial transactions with countries
blacklisted by the United States, according to a report in the
Washington Post today.
</P>
<P>
By exempting Sudan, the U.S. government cleared the way for
Occidental Petroleum Corp. to negotiate a part in a 930 million
U.S. dollar oil deal for a field in southern Sudan that could
contain an estimated 3.5 billion barrels.
</P>
<P>
Occidental reportedly donated more than 600,000 dollars to
political parties in the past two years, with donations split
evenly between Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
Occidental officials had no comment on the exemption. 
</P>
