<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR Envoy: Regional Plan for Refugee Solution in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Carrol Faubert, special envoy
of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) for the former
Yugoslavia, said here today that the regional plan on permanent
solutions for refugees from the region was expected in March.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, he said the last meeting of the
commissioner for refugees in Serbia, Montenegro, Croatia and the
two entities in Bosnia would be held in Belgrade on February 17,
and after that a regional plan was expected to be adopted by the
UNHCR on permanent solutions for refugees from the former Yugoslav
republics.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 2 million refugees or displaced persons
caused by the ex-Yugoslav crisis that started in 1991. About
700,000 have sought asylum in countries outside the former
Yugoslavia, more than 600,000 have been housed in the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia and around 1 million stay in Bosnia. Only
200,000 refugees have managed to return home since peace was
established a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Faubert, who arrived here Tuesday on a several-day visit, said
he talked with Yugoslav officials about how to accelerate the
process of return of refugees, and about possibilities of local
integration.
</P>
<P>
"We assess as positive the possibility given to refugees to
submit a demand for Yugoslav citizenship," he said.
</P>
<P>
Many refugees in Yugoslavia, fearing possible prejudice or new
conflicts, would rather stay where they are and integrate into the
local community than go back to the place of their origin in
Croatia or Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Faubert said the UNHCR considered the best solution for
refugees would be that all former Yugoslav republics made
provisions to grant dual citizenship to the refugees.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the problem of refugee repatriation to Croatia
and Bosnia-Herzegovina, Faubert said he believed the key factor
was "the readiness of political leaders to accept decisions of all
agreements signed so far, from Dayton to the Erdut agreement."
</P>
<P>
"The process of transition in the territory of Eastern Slavonia
is a good example and I think we should not be doubtful about its
success," Faubert said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970124.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Sworn In as Secretary of State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Madeleine Albright was sworn
in today as secretary of state by taking the oath of office from
Vice President Al gore at the White House.
</P>
<P>
The first female secretary of state ever in U.S. history was
confirmed to take the post by a Senate voting 99-0 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At the swearing-in ceremony, Albright promised to help lead the
United States in playing a leadership role in world affairs,
somewhat like a world policeman, even though the Clinton
administration had never acknowledged the role.
</P>
<P>
"If we are complacent or timid or unwilling to look beyond our
borders, our citizens will not prosper, and the framework of
American leadership and the foundation of American security we
have built could crumble with 21st century speed," she said.
</P>
<P>
Albright, a Czechoslovak-born daughter of a Czech envoy who
fled to the United States in 1948, had served as Clinton's U.N.
ambassador since 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
