<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Renews Warning Against Israeli Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 23 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official
today renewed warning against the grave consequences of the
Israeli policy on the Jewish settlements and Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting this afternoon with African ambassadors to
Egypt, Saeb Erekat, minister of Local Government of the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA), said that the Israeli policy
on settlement expansion on the Palestinian lands and
non-withdrawal from Jerusalem hinders the peace process and could
blow it up.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu has recently warned
of "severe consequences" if a Palestinian state is established
and vowed to keep Jerusalem as Israel's "sole and undivided
capital."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's rejection of the establishment of the Palestinian
state contradicts with the declaration of principles signed by
Israel and the Palestine Liberation Organization in Oslo, Norway
in 1993, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want to establish their own independent state
with East Jerusalem as its capital when the interim agreements
are completed by May 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Hebron issue was among 34 outstanding issues that need to
be settled, including the agreement on the safe corridor between
Gaza and the West Bank, the opening of the Gaza Airport and
harbor, taxes and financial transactions, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Israel has not abided by its commitments, and negotiations
will start in this respect," he added.
</P>
<P>
Though the road ahead is still long and rough, the Hebron deal
and negotiations will be an example to be followed in tackling
other issues, especially after the U.S. has provided guarantee to
the Israeli-Palestinian agreements, he said.
</P>
<P>
The entire issue of Jewish settlements will be discussed during
the final phase talks, due to start in mid-March, in conformity
with the Hebron protocol, added the PNA official.
</P>
<P>
Erekat called upon the African countries to continue their
support to the Palestinian people until the independent state is
established.
</P>
<P>
He met afterwards with the ambassadors of Latin America in the
Embassy of Argentina in Egypt to expound the dimensions of the
Hebron agreement and the perils facing the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Erekat came here on a two-day visit Wednesday, while PNA
President Yasser Arafat made a several hours' trip here the same
day on his first visit to Egypt since the handover of most of
Hebron to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving here, Arafat said that he was soliciting
Egyptian and Arab support for the next stage of
Israeli-Palestinian talks.
</P>
<P>
The PNA now controls the Gaza Strip and eight West Bank towns
handed over by Israel under several agreements signed since
1993. It will control 99 percent of the West Bank after completion
of the third phase of Israeli troop redeployment in the first half
of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The issue of the final status of these areas, which Israel
captured in the 1967 Mideast War, together with other sensitive
problems such as Jerusalem, refugees and the Palestinian
statehood, is to be determined in the talks which should end no
later than May 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
