<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key Issues of Georgian Peace Process Remain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 23 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said today that the key issues of the Georgian peace
process, such as the future political status of Abkhazia and the
return of refugees and displaced persons, remain unresolved.
</P>
<P>
In a report to the Security Council concerning the situation in
Abkhazia, Georgia, the secretary-general recommended that the
Security Council extend the mandate of the United Nations Observer
Mission in Georgia, stating that both sides had recently
reaffirmed their desire for a political solution.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the desirability of a political solution has also
been underlined in the increasingly frequent direct contacts
between the two parties, the secretary-general appealed to both
sides to intensify the search for a peaceful solution by further
expanding their bilateral contacts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
